[Amit Varma]: was, you know, how do you manage to write so much history? So you know, on what's your

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:19.440
[Amit Varma]: normal day like? How do you find things to read? How do you kind of go? I'm actually

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:24.000
[Guest]: quite glad that this is a podcast, not a video, because people could see me just now, to be

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.120
[Guest]: able to see the dark circles and the horrible hair and all of that. That's, you know, it's

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:32.480
[Guest]: one of those things, which is that there's a lot of reading, yet fairly isolating. When

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:36.920
[Guest]: I'm in one of my research cycles, it's 12 hours, 11 hours, 12 hours of research work

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:40.480
[Guest]: where you go to the library, say at nine in the morning, and you only get up by 830 when

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:45.720
[Guest]: the library really shuts. And all that time you're sitting at a desk, not uttering a word,

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:49.960
[Guest]: and everyone around you is silent as well. And then you just plot through all the books

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:55.360
[Guest]: that you need to gather information from. But then writing that phase is also equally

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:59.400
[Guest]: equally taxing, because what happens is then again, you know, it's sitting down and getting

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:04.000
[Guest]: the first draft done means weeks and weeks and weeks of not moving from a desk, locking

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.160
[Guest]: myself up in a room, surviving on chocolates and sweets, because that gives you energy

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:13.120
[Guest]: highs, which is sugar is poison. Yeah, but it's useful at certain times. It's one of

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:16.600
[Guest]: those phases. And then, you know, after that, of course, comes the fun, because once the

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:21.040
[Guest]: book is done, once this whole cycle of writing, the research, the writing, the editing, the

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:26.120
[Guest]: actual publishing happens, then you have the lit fests and the events and things like that,

00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:29.120
[Guest]: which is fun, because finally, you can go back to being an extrovert, you can go back

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:33.200
[Guest]: to talking to people, seeing people having fun, having your glass of champagne and things

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:37.400
[Amit Varma]: like that. So it's really very compartmentalized. Are you kind of naturally an extrovert who

00:06:37.400 --> 00:06:41.360
[Amit Varma]: likes to be social and you do you have to force yourself? Yeah, I mean, I don't think

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:44.680
[Guest]: sitting in a library for 12 hours a day is easy for me. It wasn't earlier, at least.

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:49.160
[Guest]: But with my first book, I got six years of practice. And then now things have become

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:53.440
[Amit Varma]: a little easier because I've picked up speed. And the ivory throne, of course, is 700 pages.

00:06:53.440 --> 00:07:01.360
[Guest]: This book is only 350. No, this is 383. I think the text is. Yeah, I always have lots

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:06.960
[Amit Varma]: of pages devoted to notes. Yeah, which are great and most readable. So I was just curious,

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:12.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, this book is really a collection of your columns in an expanded version plus additional

00:07:12.280 --> 00:07:17.280
[Amit Varma]: material. And I'm just wondering, since you write a weekly column for mint, how difficult

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:21.520
[Amit Varma]: does that make it in terms of the research? Because typically, I'd imagine when you research

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:25.680
[Amit Varma]: a book, it's one subject, you get 50 books on that one subject and you dive right in.

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:29.280
[Amit Varma]: But each of the columns is about something completely separate different periods. How

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:32.960
[Guest]: do you manage that? So one of the things is, you know, for the last several years, I've

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:37.640
[Guest]: made it a habit that every time I read something, I make notes, whatever book it is, no matter

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:41.800
[Guest]: where it comes from, I end up making notes. So for example, you know, I did a column once

00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:45.840
[Guest]: on Jinnah because I 12,000 words of notes on him, even though I never really intended

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:49.240
[Guest]: to do anything, which just happens that I have that much in notes sitting in a Word

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:53.120
[Guest]: document in my computer. So every week when I have to do my column, I just open up my

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:56.680
[Guest]: archives if I can't think of anything, and then you know, pull out something from there

00:07:56.680 --> 00:08:01.880
[Guest]: and use that to come up with a new topic. You know, so that's that's the usual process

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:06.520
[Guest]: every week and because it's history does require a certain amount of integrity, a certain amount

00:08:06.520 --> 00:08:10.560
[Guest]: of focus and so on, because it's a time when lots of people can write very loose history,

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:14.880
[Guest]: you can do your Google and your Google Books at most and think that you've got everything,

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:18.880
[Guest]: but it takes a little bit more. So even in this collection, for example, there's you

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:22.320
[Guest]: know, one of the essays on Savarkar, it's archival material. It's all based on material

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:26.720
[Guest]: I found in the British archives quite randomly. Other stuff, for example, is from secondary

00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:30.760
[Guest]: material and maybe a few books that I've read. A lot of it is from J store and sources like

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:35.000
[Guest]: that where they have academic journals. And my job then is to color all of this and not

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.040
[Guest]: simplify it, but make it more appealing, make it more engaging. Try and tell it like a story

00:08:40.040 --> 00:08:43.960
[Guest]: so that people are interested. But even then it's a two step process because what happens

00:08:43.960 --> 00:08:49.640
[Guest]: is usually a column ends up being written in about 2000 words 1500 to 2000. Then have

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:53.960
[Guest]: to keep pulling it down to 1000 which is my word limit for mint because the print newspaper

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:58.040
[Guest]: right so there's a fixed space allocated for it. And you know, in the first six months

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:01.680
[Guest]: it used to be a challenge because I'd fight with them saying give me 200 words extra give

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:05.200
[Guest]: me this, you know, 50 words extra. And even now I occasionally get emails saying can you

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.920
[Guest]: chop off 30 words here or 20 words there? Because it's all Yeah, so the original versions

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:14.280
[Guest]: were filed away quietly. And then when two or three publishers started showing interest

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:17.640
[Guest]: in the columns themselves, I said, Well, you know, there are longer versions might as well

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:22.000
[Amit Varma]: use that. So yeah, and what's the process of reading like, like, imagine on one hand,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:25.440
[Amit Varma]: if you're sort of researching, you're doing deep reading, you're reading really carefully

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:29.200
[Amit Varma]: taking notes. But on the other hand, you have a lot of material to get through, especially

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:34.200
[Amit Varma]: if this historical material, there's a temptation to just skim through stuff. How do you manage

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:38.880
[Guest]: that? Yeah, I mean, as I said, the first six years because my first book required me to

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:42.440
[Guest]: sort of sit in the archives in the library for hours and hours and hours, and devote

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:46.600
[Guest]: the first half of my 20s to that whole process. I've picked up a degree of speed in the sense

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:50.400
[Guest]: that you know, I can get through say one book in two days or a day and a half. Because I'm

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:54.320
[Guest]: not reading it for pleasure. I know exactly what I'm looking for. I know, when I see a

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:57.640
[Guest]: fact whether or not I use it, I don't know. But I know that fact is interesting. So I

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:01.240
[Guest]: know how to take it out and put it into my notes. So most of the time it's quotes, I

00:10:01.240 --> 00:10:05.760
[Guest]: just lift quotes out of any book that I read, and put them in a word doc. And then I can

00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:09.200
[Guest]: go back to them because I've got the words as they are. So mechanically, you can type

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:13.440
[Guest]: up a good chunk of the of the book, and keep it there. And then whenever you revisit it,

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:17.760
[Guest]: you can actually properly digest it. How much do you read? How many books do you read in

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:23.200
[Guest]: a month? This I can't say, because I never counted. But I do remember, when I did one

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:27.400
[Guest]: of my when I was 23, I did this BBC project called Incarnations. I was a researcher for

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:33.640
[Guest]: Sunil Khilnani. I think at that time, I'd read for that whole project about 450 books.

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:37.080
[Guest]: Because you know, how much time? I don't know, about eight months or something like that.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:40.960
[Guest]: So it was, it was something. So yeah, there are there are lots of books. My next book,

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:44.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, I've already got an archive of some 400 odd books. And how do you how do you get

00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:48.880
[Guest]: these books from like, what's the process? So you know, when I was in London, the British

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.440
[Guest]: Library is a huge archive, the School of Oriental and African Studies, they have a lot of India

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:56.760
[Guest]: related material, the LSE library has stuff. In India, there's, you know, the Mandarkar

00:10:56.760 --> 00:11:01.960
[Guest]: Institute exists, there's the Gokhale Institute, a lot of it is now available online, for example,

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:06.280
[Guest]: Gokhale Institute's library is digitizing most of their stuff. So a lot of old books

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:10.600
[Guest]: in Marathi, Hindi, they're all available online. So you know, you can therefore access them

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:11.600
[Amit Varma]: wherever you are.

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:15.480
[Amit Varma]: But say, if you're a kid sitting in, if you're a kid sitting in Patna or Madurai or something,

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:19.360
[Amit Varma]: and you want to be a historian, and you'll have some kind of access to all of this.

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:22.720
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it would be wiser than to seek an institution which would then support you

00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:26.760
[Guest]: and give you institutional access, being part of a university or part of some sort of bigger

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:31.440
[Guest]: institution helps, it opens doors more easily than otherwise, because otherwise, a lot of

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:34.440
[Guest]: libraries, you know, they're also resource crunched. So unless you're actually you look

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:38.440
[Guest]: serious, they may not think that you're worth giving that sort of attention and time to

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:42.440
[Amit Varma]: you. Right. So, you know, one of the sort of interesting things that struck me as I

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:46.540
[Amit Varma]: started reading your book, and one of your early essays is called a Marathi princess

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:51.360
[Amit Varma]: morality play from which I, you know, took the story at the start of the episode. And

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:57.920
[Amit Varma]: just reading it, it struck me in how richly diverse not just India is, but how regions

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:02.680
[Amit Varma]: in India are, for example, when you talk about this 12 year old Maratha boy, who is the ruler

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:07.700
[Amit Varma]: of Tamil Tanjavur, you also mentioned quote, the event was emblematic of India in this

00:12:07.700 --> 00:12:13.400
[Amit Varma]: bustling age with Tamil Nadu alone, attracting Afghan horsemen, Bundela Rajputs, Telugu warriors

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:19.000
[Amit Varma]: and other varieties of adventurers, stop quote, and this is kind of a theme going through

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.480
[Guest]: all your books, right? Yeah, in fact, since you mentioned this Maratha prince, what's

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:26.360
[Guest]: interesting is now he's a Maratha, he's Shiraji's nephew, which is, you know, it's a fairly

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:30.520
[Guest]: glamorous uncle to have. And he's established power in Tanjavur where the people speak Tamil.

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:34.760
[Guest]: But what's his code language is Telugu, because the Marathas over there continue patronizing

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:38.760
[Guest]: Telugu, which had great prestige attached to it. So it's a it's a multicultural court,

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:42.720
[Guest]: you know, that existed in the 18th century. And what's even more striking is that, you

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:46.080
[Guest]: know, you in your introduction, you read out this bit about where this lady where the man

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:50.080
[Guest]: with the Brahmin says that, you know, we drink cow's milk, you eat the entire cow, so you

00:12:50.080 --> 00:12:54.000
[Guest]: must be more pure. This is the kind of statement you can't say anymore. Imagine if a playwright

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.560
[Guest]: said that today, there'd be a lot of scandal and chaos around it, because it's insulting

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:02.180
[Guest]: and people are waiting to take offense and this and that. But this is Shiraji's nephew

00:13:02.180 --> 00:13:07.320
[Guest]: saying it in the early 18th century, a man who was born, you know, in the late 17th century,

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:11.440
[Guest]: he's the one saying this. And, you know, clearly, we had more of a sense of humor then. And

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:15.440
[Guest]: yeah, the world was a much more diverse place. The South India was much more diverse. And

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:19.400
[Guest]: it wasn't surprising in South India, because it's a peninsula, peninsulas tend to have

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:23.480
[Guest]: people who come from various places. So the idea of a foreigner is not such a scandalous

00:13:23.480 --> 00:13:27.640
[Guest]: concept in the south, maybe in the north, which is landlocked, these things may be different,

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:31.440
[Guest]: but in the south, and even in the north, you know, you find all these big imperial cities,

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:36.280
[Guest]: it's impossible, you will end up having Ottoman artillery men, you'll end up having, you know,

00:13:36.280 --> 00:13:39.600
[Guest]: all kinds of mercenaries from all kinds of places. One of the essays in this book is

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:44.560
[Guest]: about Begum Samru. You know, this is a notch girl of Kashmiri descent, married first to

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:48.320
[Guest]: a German, then to a Frenchman in the middle, she has an affair with an Irishman. What were

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:52.520
[Guest]: these foreigners doing here? They were all mercenaries. They were all military men who

00:13:52.520 --> 00:13:56.800
[Guest]: served Indian Maharajas. The Sindhiyas of Gwalior had I think a German under serving

00:13:56.800 --> 00:14:01.280
[Guest]: under them. The Maharaja of Travanco in Kerala had a Dutch man who came and sort of modernized

00:14:01.280 --> 00:14:05.680
[Guest]: his army. So everywhere you look, there is this sort of foreign presence. So it's not

00:14:05.680 --> 00:14:09.720
[Guest]: just Indians moving about within the country, elite Indians, to be fair, we're not talking

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:15.080
[Guest]: about lower class or lower caste groups. This is people with access to power and mobility.

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:18.080
[Guest]: You not only have them moving around different areas, but you also have lots of foreigners

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:21.800
[Guest]: coming in from overseas and becoming pretty much part of this society.

00:14:21.800 --> 00:14:27.240
[Amit Varma]: And it also seemed to me that, you know, without a constitution that protects free speech,

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:33.600
[Amit Varma]: there was actually a lot of fearless parodying and, you know, satire happening. For example,

00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:39.800
[Amit Varma]: at one point, you talk about Nyanadev creating this buffalo that produces Vedic sounds or

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:44.000
[Amit Varma]: sounds that sounds like a story. Yeah, that's a story. And you and you have stuff like that

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.680
[Amit Varma]: coming out. So is it sort of a selective reading to look at all of this great satire and say

00:14:48.680 --> 00:14:53.040
[Amit Varma]: that, hey, it was easy to kind of stand up against or is it selection bias?

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:56.600
[Guest]: I think Yeah, I think you can't say it was easy because it was always challenging. It

00:14:56.600 --> 00:14:59.960
[Guest]: always took a degree of courage, especially when it came to caste. Now, you find the funny

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:03.840
[Guest]: thing is that, you know, there's this time in the 19th century when Jyotiba Phule says

00:15:03.840 --> 00:15:07.920
[Guest]: that, you know, the Brahmins claim that they came out of the creator, the cosmic creator's

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:12.120
[Guest]: head, whereas the Shudras came from the feet and so on. So does that mean the cosmic creator

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:16.320
[Guest]: also menstruates from the mouth? He actually asked that in the 19th century. What's interesting

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:21.000
[Guest]: is that when when Kabir was there a few centuries before, he said, you know, the Brahmins claim

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.360
[Guest]: they came from they come from the head. So does that mean there was a special birth canal

00:15:24.360 --> 00:15:29.160
[Guest]: through the creator's ear? You know, he said that Basava in the 12th century said something

00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:33.040
[Guest]: very similar. And he also famously said that, you know, with the loaded with the weight

00:15:33.040 --> 00:15:37.320
[Guest]: of their Vedas, the Brahmin is a veritable donkey. Now, these are things you can say,

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:41.800
[Guest]: but you also need a degree of clout and privilege already. With Kabir, he was persecuted. Phule,

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:46.000
[Guest]: of course, didn't get very popular with Brahmins in Maharashtra, especially, you know, powerful

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.400
[Guest]: ones like Tilak, for example, they had more of a hold on public imagination. But there

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:55.800
[Guest]: was space for polemics, there was space to think and stand up and object. And people

00:15:55.800 --> 00:16:01.080
[Guest]: who managed to do that when the caste system was at its most rigid and powerful, I think

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:04.520
[Guest]: there's something really magical that they managed to pull off. Because they said that

00:16:04.520 --> 00:16:08.800
[Guest]: then we are now able to sit and have this conversation in a time where this is now,

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:11.760
[Guest]: you know, you're not supposed to say these things and so on. But we can always say, look,

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:15.360
[Guest]: I'm not saying it. These people said that before me. So I'm being part of a tradition

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:20.440
[Guest]: that is much longer, where as much as this, this Brahminical order or the caste systems exist,

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:26.280
[Guest]: there's been that much of a resistance also, throughout the last 1000 years, it's always

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:30.080
[Guest]: been there every now and then there's a spokesperson standing up and saying this is bad, which

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:33.800
[Guest]: means the challenge is always there. There was an article recently that said, you know,

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:38.080
[Guest]: and there's this notion that caste is a British invention. It's not true. The British in some

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:43.120
[Guest]: ways solidified and rigidized it some more, they sort of established in paper as though

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:47.440
[Guest]: this is the final version of the caste system and created their own trouble in that system.

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:51.640
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean the caste system didn't exist before that caste existed before that.

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:55.560
[Guest]: Some castes sometimes became richer or poorer and that sort of thing. And you could sometimes

00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:59.840
[Guest]: change your Varna status, you know, like a lot of kings go from being Shudras to Kshatriyas

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:03.400
[Guest]: by performing certain rituals, but that doesn't make caste go away. You know, you look at

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:08.400
[Guest]: the corpus of Bhakti literature, it's all about standing up to caste and ritualism and,

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:12.440
[Guest]: and social, you know, order that's based on discrimination.

00:17:12.440 --> 00:17:16.680
[Amit Varma]: And that's, in fact, one of the great revelations of this book, how through various parts of

00:17:16.680 --> 00:17:22.000
[Amit Varma]: it, you realize that long before Western modernity came to India, long before the influences

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.480
[Amit Varma]: of the Enlightenment came to India, there were free thinkers and rationalists who were

00:17:25.480 --> 00:17:31.280
[Amit Varma]: challenging existing structures fairly bravely, you know, reading your book, like because

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:38.040
[Amit Varma]: there are 61 discrete chapters, 61 stories, the way I read it was, I started making notes

00:17:38.040 --> 00:17:42.480
[Amit Varma]: with each chapter and trying to figure out which themes run across it. And two of the

00:17:42.480 --> 00:17:47.000
[Amit Varma]: strong themes that sort of run through your book, which I'll probably use to as a means

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.440
[Amit Varma]: of convenience to structure this episode, are caste and gender. And I'm sure you did

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:55.960
[Amit Varma]: not set out looking for any of these, it's just that when you tell these stories, they

00:17:55.960 --> 00:18:02.200
[Amit Varma]: are just there. And it's it's impossible not to notice their impact. And in many cases,

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:07.320
[Amit Varma]: the protagonists of the stories themselves are sort of unaware of their impact. And in

00:18:07.320 --> 00:18:12.880
[Amit Varma]: some cases, they are manipulating it. For example, your your book begins with this story

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:19.400
[Amit Varma]: of the gentleman named Roberto Danubili. Is that the right pronunciation? Yeah, the Italian

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:27.560
[Amit Varma]: who comes to South India to convert people and quickly realizes that he has to take the

00:18:27.560 --> 00:18:31.680
[Amit Varma]: angle of caste into consideration to become an effective converter. Tell me a little bit

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:34.960
[Guest]: more about it. It's quite fascinating, because this guy is born in Italy into this aristocratic,

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:39.000
[Guest]: you know, powerful family. He's got a Holy Roman Emperor in his family tree, there's

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:43.400
[Guest]: a pope in his family tree, a good Catholic as it were, his parents wanted to continue

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:47.320
[Guest]: the line and so on. But he decides he wants to become a missionary. Now he runs away from

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:53.600
[Guest]: home becomes a priest and then eventually ends up coming to Goa, from where he comes

00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:57.480
[Guest]: down to Madurai. Now that's a very strange location, because Madurai there's been a mission

00:18:57.480 --> 00:19:00.740
[Guest]: set up by this much older man a few years before, but they managed to convert barely

00:19:00.740 --> 00:19:06.520
[Guest]: anybody. And this man comes and realizes that one of the reasons is that now the previous

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:10.760
[Guest]: Jesuit who was there was eating beef. He was a parangi, a foreigner, so you know, the Brahmins

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:14.720
[Guest]: and the elite sort of kept a distance. Whereas this man said that I'm going to use I'm going

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:19.200
[Guest]: to become somewhat more Sanskritic myself. So he starts wearing the poonool or the sacred

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:24.140
[Guest]: thread or the janeo which is now you know, you had Rahul Gandhi flaunting it recently.

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:29.000
[Guest]: He starts wearing the saffron robes of a sanyasi. He starts eating out of a plantain leaf rather

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.440
[Guest]: than a plate because a plate is too European, a plantain leaf is local. He starts learning

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:37.400
[Guest]: Telugu and Tamil and starts debating Brahmins in their own language. He starts, I mean,

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:41.600
[Guest]: he doesn't appreciate the Vedas, but he learns the Vedas, he tries to get a basic sense of

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:46.580
[Guest]: it. So he makes a lot of effort to understand what the society is, and then finally decides

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:51.720
[Guest]: to start converting Brahmins. So he converts a series of Brahmins, he converts a prince,

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:56.820
[Guest]: one of these local Nayaka chieftains brothers, he converts a number of high class people.

00:19:56.820 --> 00:20:00.400
[Guest]: And in his church, what he does is he again has a caste system. So the poor are all standing

00:20:00.400 --> 00:20:05.840
[Guest]: by the door, the more, you know, upper class converts are all sitting inside and he creates

00:20:05.840 --> 00:20:12.440
[Guest]: a caste system within his new sort of Tamilised Catholicism there. And the funny thing is

00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:19.320
[Guest]: the influence still exists in Catholic communities in Tamil Nadu. So you know, if you go to Chennai,

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:24.520
[Guest]: there's that Our Lady of, not Vellankanni, there's a Virgin Mary there, but they dress

00:20:24.520 --> 00:20:28.800
[Guest]: her up in a sari and there is a chariot festival and all of that, which essentially is a lot

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:33.360
[Guest]: like Hindu goddess temples and you know, their chariot processions and all of that happens.

00:20:33.360 --> 00:20:36.980
[Guest]: In Kerala also, you find that, you know, the Christians there, the old Syrian Christians

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:42.900
[Guest]: have a lot of Hindu customs that exist within their Christian everyday ritualistic practices.

00:20:42.900 --> 00:20:46.000
[Guest]: So this man does something like that. And he says that I'm going to become a Hindu to

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.440
[Guest]: save the Hindus and make them Christians. So you know, it provokes this big debate on

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:55.640
[Guest]: whether or not when you convert, you should convert completely, not just in terms of what

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:59.640
[Guest]: God you believe in, but in terms of your outer expression of who you are and what clothes

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:04.680
[Guest]: you wear and so on. And this continues even to the 19th century. You know, I've got other,

00:21:04.680 --> 00:21:08.920
[Guest]: it's not in this book, but as part of my research, even in the late 19th century, you know, there

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:13.960
[Guest]: were converts in Maharashtra, in Tamil Nadu, in Chennai and so on, who were converting,

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:16.840
[Guest]: but they were still holding on to their sacred thread because they said we're converting,

00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:21.520
[Guest]: but this is a social mark. Our sacred thread evokes the image of our original caste position

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:24.880
[Guest]: as Brahmins. So, you know, they didn't see any reason why converting to Christianity

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:28.880
[Guest]: would cause them to give up their Poonul. But you know, such as that, that was what

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:32.920
[Guest]: this Roberto started off and ended up, you know, he was this Italian Brahmin pretending

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:38.040
[Guest]: that the Bible was this lost Veda and he was part of this Brahminical tradition himself.

00:21:38.040 --> 00:21:41.240
[Guest]: And to a great extent, he succeeded because by the end of his career, there were about

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:46.440
[Guest]: 4,000-5,000 converts that he had managed to make where earlier there were only a few dozens.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:50.000
[Guest]: And he was thrown into prison. He did have some difficulties, but he somehow managed

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:56.280
[Guest]: to push through and he also got the Pope at the time to acknowledge and support his methods.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:22:00.440
[Guest]: Of course, by the next century after his death, another Pope revoked that permission and these

00:22:00.440 --> 00:22:05.560
[Guest]: Malabar rites, as they were called, were banned, but it left its impact. You know, even now

00:22:05.560 --> 00:22:09.480
[Guest]: the right-wing hates him because they think he came here as some sort of sinister agent

00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:14.360
[Guest]: with the desire to sort of penetrate society and, you know, convert people like that. Of

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:17.240
[Guest]: course, that's what he did. But I don't think he came here with such grand plans. It's just

00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:20.920
[Guest]: that he decided that he was going to live here and die here. So he might as well become

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:24.760
[Amit Varma]: Indian in many ways. In fact, while reading it, I thought that the right-wing today should

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:28.600
[Amit Varma]: love him because he, you know, he spoke about how the Bible was a lost Veda, which kind

00:22:28.600 --> 00:22:32.280
[Amit Varma]: of reminded me of what the right-wing says about, you know, Christianity originating

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:38.120
[Amit Varma]: as Krishna Niti and all of that. And one of the sort of meta themes that also seems to

00:22:38.120 --> 00:22:43.920
[Amit Varma]: run through your book is narrative manipulation. For example, here, he's figuring out that

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:49.280
[Amit Varma]: he's got to use a caste as a tactic and sort of, and therefore he creates this narrative

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:54.120
[Amit Varma]: where Christianity kind of fits into that. And throughout the book, you have characters

00:22:54.120 --> 00:22:57.840
[Amit Varma]: who are recasting themselves. Of course, one constant form of narrative manipulation is

00:22:57.840 --> 00:23:04.080
[Amit Varma]: what is done to women, how they are recast into sort of more conventional and acceptable

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:09.520
[Amit Varma]: avatars, as it were. And, you know, you have Shivaji recasting himself through the thing

00:23:09.520 --> 00:23:14.320
[Amit Varma]: you have, you know, all the different narratives around Kabir's birth, where he's born a Hindu,

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:18.560
[Guest]: born a Muslim. And nobody's quite, I mean, everyone wants to claim him. Everyone wants

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:24.200
[Amit Varma]: to claim him. Getting back to caste, another fascinating chapter was called a Dalit at

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:31.360
[Amit Varma]: the temple door, which is about a gentleman named Chokmila in Pandharpur, who is a bhakti

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:38.400
[Amit Varma]: saint, basically. The first mahar, the first male mahar bhakti saint. Yeah. And you quote

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:43.560
[Amit Varma]: him at one point as, you know, complaining to the Brahmin gatekeepers of the temple where

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:48.760
[Amit Varma]: he isn't allowed in. And he says, the cane is crooked, but its juice isn't crooked. Chokha

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:55.000
[Amit Varma]: is ugly, but his feelings aren't ugly. Why be fooled by outward appearance? Tell me a

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:01.600
[Amit Varma]: little bit about Chokmila and how he sort of became one of the big bhakti saints. Yeah,

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:06.080
[Guest]: he and what's interesting is that he doesn't quite challenge the status quo in the way

00:24:06.080 --> 00:24:10.520
[Guest]: say Atukaram does or, you know, some of the other bhakti saints do, because at the end

00:24:10.520 --> 00:24:14.440
[Guest]: of the day, they still had relative social position and privilege. So, you know, even

00:24:14.440 --> 00:24:19.200
[Guest]: Atukaram, even though he was, you know, from his family were grocers and they were shudras,

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:23.000
[Guest]: but they were not atishudras, as Phule would put it later. They were not absolute Dalits.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:27.880
[Guest]: A mahar means he's a menial worker. That's his job, you know, dragging away dead cows

00:24:27.880 --> 00:24:31.560
[Guest]: and their carcasses and things like that. And one of his stories, it's funny, you know,

00:24:31.560 --> 00:24:35.720
[Guest]: God appears to lend him a hand to drag away this dead cow. So he therefore doesn't have

00:24:35.720 --> 00:24:40.280
[Guest]: the privilege to quite say things that are too direct and too blunt, because his position

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:44.600
[Guest]: is already very weak. So anything he says he can be knocked off quite easily as opposed

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:49.300
[Guest]: to others with some protection. So as a result of that, there's a little bit of fatalism

00:24:49.300 --> 00:24:53.100
[Guest]: in his message, which is that, oh, you know, this is, I must be born in this position because

00:24:53.100 --> 00:24:57.440
[Guest]: of my past karma, and things like that. His son, Karmamela is not so forgiving. Karmamela

00:24:57.440 --> 00:25:01.440
[Guest]: is much more direct saying, you know, what kind of God are you, if this is the fate you've

00:25:01.440 --> 00:25:07.200
[Guest]: sort of, you know, compared us or forced us into. Whereas Chokamela is a little more accepting.

00:25:07.200 --> 00:25:10.640
[Guest]: He believes that in his past life, he's done something wrong. That's why this is happening.

00:25:10.640 --> 00:25:15.200
[Guest]: But at the end of the day, the closest he can get to his God is to the temple door.

00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:19.040
[Guest]: He's not allowed anywhere beyond that. And the story is that, you know, he was finally

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:23.200
[Guest]: asked to go and do some work and there was an accident there and he was buried alive.

00:25:23.200 --> 00:25:27.240
[Guest]: And he pulled his body out and even his bones were chanting God's name. That's the story.

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:30.400
[Guest]: So they finally got his remains and buried it. They said, you can't bury it inside the

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:33.840
[Guest]: temple because it's impure. So we'll bury it at the door. And that's why even today

00:25:33.840 --> 00:25:37.520
[Guest]: there is a shrine to Chokamela. The funny thing is, by the 18th century, this is where

00:25:37.520 --> 00:25:42.400
[Guest]: Dalits used to gather and, you know, worship the deity. And that's when the Peshwas say,

00:25:42.400 --> 00:25:46.000
[Guest]: no, no, you can't stand near the entrance because all the Brahmins going in, you know,

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:50.240
[Guest]: your sweat and your bodies are touching them. So it's impure. So you guys have got to move

00:25:50.240 --> 00:25:53.640
[Guest]: from here. So, you know, the end of the day, Chokamela, all his life, all he wanted was

00:25:53.640 --> 00:25:58.480
[Guest]: a glimpse of the deity inside. And although the deity often came out and met him in miraculous

00:25:58.480 --> 00:26:02.720
[Guest]: situations, sometimes sitting with him, sometimes, you know, helping him with his work and so

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:06.720
[Guest]: on. Even the deity doesn't tell him, OK, break the law, you know, enter the temple, let's

00:26:06.720 --> 00:26:10.560
[Guest]: see what happens. Because at the end of the day, you know, I think Chokamela was a little

00:26:10.560 --> 00:26:14.960
[Guest]: paranoid about making anything, taking a step that was too dramatic. Because, you know,

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:20.800
[Guest]: this is what caste does. You assume that it was some sort of flexible system and so on.

00:26:20.800 --> 00:26:25.240
[Guest]: It wasn't. He didn't have the privilege. He couldn't have said what he wanted to say.

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:29.520
[Guest]: As I said, Abbaswana earlier could in the 12th century say, call a Brahmin a veritable

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:33.540
[Guest]: donkey loaded with his Vedas because he was a Brahmin himself. He was born a Brahmin.

00:26:33.540 --> 00:26:37.720
[Guest]: So he could get away with saying it because he was protected by that much privilege. Chokamela

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:41.080
[Guest]: never could say something like that because he would probably have been lynched. So some

00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:46.880
[Amit Varma]: things in this country obviously never change. Never change. And what happened to Chokamela's

00:26:46.880 --> 00:26:50.600
[Guest]: son? Is he remembered? Not very much. Because the thing is, because his message has a little

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:54.880
[Guest]: more punch, he isn't sung that much during these Varkari processions and so on. He's

00:26:54.880 --> 00:27:00.040
[Guest]: not a very major figure. So it's Chokamela on the other hand people like because he doesn't,

00:27:00.040 --> 00:27:04.840
[Guest]: you know, his devotion overtakes any hint of radicalism that may have been there. There

00:27:04.840 --> 00:27:09.400
[Guest]: are occasional times, like the quote that you read out, there are occasional times where

00:27:09.400 --> 00:27:13.560
[Guest]: Chokamela seems to question the social order. But broadly, he's, you know, not going to

00:27:13.560 --> 00:27:18.640
[Guest]: push too hard. So he's a little more popular because the powers that be could come to terms

00:27:18.640 --> 00:27:24.760
[Guest]: with him. But his son is a little too blunt. So his son is slightly less, let's say recalled.

00:27:24.760 --> 00:27:30.360
[Amit Varma]: So like you said, Basava being a Brahmin himself, could then, you know, say things like quote

00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:34.920
[Amit Varma]: false, utterly false are the stories of divine birth, the higher type of man is a man who

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:40.240
[Amit Varma]: knows himself, stop quote. And at another point, he says, quote, on the same earth stands

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:45.000
[Amit Varma]: the outcasts Havel and the deity's temple, whether for ritual or rinsing, is not the

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:49.920
[Amit Varma]: water same, stop quote. And like you said, it's it's purely because of his Brahmin birth

00:27:49.920 --> 00:27:53.760
[Amit Varma]: that he could do this. I mean, otherwise, you know, he would have been lynched. Yeah.

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:58.280
[Guest]: And his people also, they were finally attacked. And they had to sort of flee when they arranged

00:27:58.280 --> 00:28:02.520
[Guest]: an intercaste marriage where they got a Brahmin's daughter married to an untouchable son. That

00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:05.840
[Guest]: is not only intercaste, it's I mean, if it was a man marrying an untouchable woman, I

00:28:05.840 --> 00:28:09.280
[Guest]: suppose some people would have still swallowed it. But a Brahmin woman might be given to

00:28:09.280 --> 00:28:13.320
[Guest]: an untouchable man. This is in the 12th century. Imagine, you know, even today in this country,

00:28:13.320 --> 00:28:17.080
[Guest]: there was a news report a few days ago for 17 or 18 year old boy killing his 21 year

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:21.480
[Guest]: old sister, shooting her in the head or something because she'd married someone below caste.

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:26.200
[Guest]: And that's happening now in 2019. And in Basavastan, in the 12th century also, when a Brahmin woman

00:28:26.200 --> 00:28:31.760
[Guest]: married an untouchable, this was the kind of reaction, his entire community was uprooted

00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:34.880
[Guest]: and there was violence and a massacre and they all had to run away and he died the next

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:40.080
[Guest]: year. And they had to essentially live underground and be very quiet and unobtrusive for many

00:28:40.080 --> 00:28:44.920
[Guest]: centuries before the Lingayats could again start asserting their identity. So even when

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:50.160
[Guest]: he finally transgressed that, that marriage aspect or the mingling of castes, interdining,

00:28:50.160 --> 00:28:54.360
[Guest]: all of that, there were repercussions. But he could say a lot more, his message could

00:28:54.360 --> 00:28:59.080
[Guest]: be a little more powerful because he was, he was a minister in a local ruler's court.

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:02.320
[Guest]: So he had that, how did he become a minister because he was a Brahmin, because he had access

00:29:02.320 --> 00:29:08.040
[Guest]: to education. So he was protected by a lot of social privilege, which gave him more of

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:12.760
[Guest]: more space to really articulate more radical thoughts. But others didn't always have that

00:29:12.760 --> 00:29:16.840
[Amit Varma]: space. Yeah. And there's a lovely, I mean, your book is of course full of lovely sentences

00:29:16.840 --> 00:29:23.480
[Amit Varma]: because, you know, there's such a entertaining sense of, there's such wit that you bring

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:26.400
[Amit Varma]: to your writing. So I'll read the sentence out about what happened to the parents of

00:29:26.400 --> 00:29:31.600
[Amit Varma]: the inter-caste couple who got married. Quote, the monarch and the establishment were apoplectic.

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:36.120
[Amit Varma]: The respective fathers, it is said, had their eyes gouged out, after which they were thrown

00:29:36.120 --> 00:29:42.160
[Amit Varma]: under elephants to painfully meet their maker, casteless in death. Stop quote. And this is

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:45.040
[Amit Varma]: a common theme through the Middle Ages, that people getting thrown under elephants.

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:48.720
[Guest]: I think it was some sort of favourite theme. Even in the early 19th century, when I was

00:29:48.720 --> 00:29:53.200
[Guest]: doing my research on my first book, there's a celebrated figure in Kerala history called

00:29:53.200 --> 00:29:58.200
[Guest]: Veluthambi Dalava. He's the man who stood up to the British in 1809. And what's interesting

00:29:58.200 --> 00:30:02.000
[Guest]: is one of his favourite formats of punishment for rebels and people who were criminals,

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:05.880
[Guest]: etc, was to tie one leg to one elephant, the other to another elephant and then drive them

00:30:05.880 --> 00:30:10.480
[Guest]: in opposite directions. So the person will be torn to bits by these two elephants. So

00:30:10.480 --> 00:30:15.120
[Guest]: the elephants, yeah, they were clearly a very popular form. And also gouging the eyes out.

00:30:15.120 --> 00:30:18.840
[Guest]: It's also common, especially among the Mughals, that if you want to get rid of a rival, you

00:30:18.840 --> 00:30:22.600
[Guest]: don't have to kill him, just blind him. Because under Islamic law, blinding makes you ineligible

00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:25.800
[Guest]: to rule. So you know, if you don't want to kill your brother, which is also an option,

00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:29.200
[Guest]: by the way, you can always kill everybody. But if you don't, then you can simply blind

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:36.120
[Amit Varma]: them and feel a little less guilty. Yeah, it's more empathetic to blind your enemies.

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:41.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, another quote from Basava, which I kind of like, which again, is about conservative

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:47.680
[Amit Varma]: Brahminical hypocrisy, as you put it. And the quote is, they say pour, pour the milk

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:52.160
[Amit Varma]: when they see a snake image in stone, but they cry kill, kill when they meet a snake

00:30:52.160 --> 00:31:00.760
[Amit Varma]: for real. Stop quote. And Basava was also very enlightened in terms of, for example,

00:31:00.760 --> 00:31:05.920
[Amit Varma]: gender, like you also write about, you know, if you want to test the sincerity of those

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:09.080
[Amit Varma]: who are trying to bring about reform, that is again, one of the litmus tests by which

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:13.720
[Amit Varma]: you can judge them, like what have they done for gender and out of the 200 saints associated

00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:19.600
[Amit Varma]: with him as many as 35 were female, 14 of them unmarried, one of them naked, you know,

00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:22.800
[Guest]: one of them naked. Yeah. So you know, she didn't she didn't wear clothes. And she was

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:26.920
[Guest]: originally married to a royal person and she eventually walks out of there. And this is

00:31:26.920 --> 00:31:30.560
[Guest]: the man who gives her refuge when her nakedness becomes a matter of controversy within the

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:34.320
[Guest]: group. He's the one who rises to defend her. Similarly, you know, this is the funny thing.

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:39.000
[Guest]: There are lots of reformers who are anti caste, but the basic caste system around the world

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:42.840
[Guest]: has been between men and women. There's always that caste system, which are which fewer people

00:31:42.840 --> 00:31:47.400
[Guest]: are willing to take on. So Basava has this had this interesting thing where usually even

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:53.000
[Guest]: in the more enlightened communities or liberated communities or whatever, menstruating women

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:57.520
[Guest]: were still considered impure. But for Linga, it's all Basava, as per his philosophy, there's

00:31:57.520 --> 00:32:00.960
[Guest]: nothing impure about it. menstruation is a perfectly natural function. That's what it

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:05.880
[Guest]: is. You can still hold your Ishta Linga, which is their totem, which is a portable Shiva

00:32:05.880 --> 00:32:09.440
[Guest]: Linga. And that was that was the only thing they don't go to temples, their dead are buried,

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:15.200
[Guest]: very different customs. But you know, menstruating women were not sin women had an almost equal

00:32:15.200 --> 00:32:19.760
[Guest]: position within his own order. Although in terms of numbers, they were not an equal half.

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:25.640
[Guest]: 35 out of a little over 200 is a fairly large number. If you look at the other, you know,

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:29.000
[Guest]: saints etc. And how many women they had around them, even Kabir sometimes could say very

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:32.440
[Guest]: sexist things, you know, calling women sin and things like that. Of course, the thing

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:36.000
[Guest]: with saints is they also say very contradictory things. So in one poem, they'll say sin the

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:40.320
[Guest]: other poem, they'll say something else. So this often happens. So the context is important

00:32:40.320 --> 00:32:44.160
[Guest]: in which something is being said. But Basava was unusual for this reason also that women

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:48.640
[Guest]: to him in that caste system also he wanted to smash it was and that may perhaps explain

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.400
[Guest]: why he was getting a Brahmin's daughter married to an untouchable son, because it was several

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:56.640
[Guest]: things that he was trying to shift and change at the same time. And in some regards, perhaps

00:32:56.640 --> 00:33:01.200
[Guest]: he was trying to do too much too quickly, because then obviously the the backlash is

00:33:01.200 --> 00:33:08.200
[Amit Varma]: also very intense. And there's also a very interesting sort of interesting theme of gender

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:12.920
[Amit Varma]: fluidity, which comes out like one of his vachanas goes, look here, dear fellow, I wear

00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:17.720
[Amit Varma]: these men's clothes only for you. Sometimes I am man, sometimes I am woman, stop quote,

00:33:17.720 --> 00:33:22.520
[Guest]: which given the times is pretty quite a lot of bhakti, actually bhakti literature, it's

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:27.600
[Guest]: often even men, they often take female voices. So you know, Shetra, yeah, who's this big

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:32.840
[Guest]: bhakti poet, a lot of Telugu work, you often have God presented as a customer on his way

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:36.160
[Guest]: to his favorite courtesan. And you have poems where the courtesan turns around saying, why

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:39.880
[Guest]: have you come to my door? I saw you at that other Radha's door the other day, you know,

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:44.400
[Guest]: go back to her and things like that. So the voice is often of this woman who's a little

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:50.280
[Guest]: annoyed with God. Otherwise, it's a love loan, you know, viraha sort of expression where

00:33:50.280 --> 00:33:54.680
[Guest]: she's pining for her beloved and the man, you know, essentially feminizes his voice,

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:58.960
[Guest]: because God is a masculine, he is the one who's missing God. But here again, you have

00:33:58.960 --> 00:34:02.920
[Guest]: the naked saint Mahadevi, you know, she says that, you know, while Basava says that she

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:07.120
[Guest]: says, no, I'm masculine. No, she identifies with the masculine, she sees herself as the

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:12.440
[Guest]: masculine principle and so on. So yeah, it's, it's interesting how much fluidity in that

00:34:12.440 --> 00:34:17.600
[Guest]: sense there was, at least in terms of articulating your thought, there was no gender didn't stand

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:22.080
[Guest]: in the way you could easily switch voices, depending on what was comfortable for your

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:26.120
[Amit Varma]: sense of expression. And the Lingayats when they formed seem to be something that was

00:34:26.120 --> 00:34:30.520
[Amit Varma]: kind of outside caste rebellion against an orthodox Hinduism, but eventually they sort

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:34.640
[Amit Varma]: of got assimilated into the mainstream and are now considered just another caste. Yeah,

00:34:34.640 --> 00:34:38.120
[Guest]: I mean, they want to break out of the Hindu fold. There was that whole thing a couple

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:42.240
[Guest]: of years ago. But you know, the thing the way caste functions is that this is what it

00:34:42.240 --> 00:34:46.240
[Guest]: does. You know, initially, even rebels are eventually made to fit into the system, caste

00:34:46.240 --> 00:34:50.240
[Guest]: doesn't break, caste just absorbs them into a new caste. You see this among Kerala Christians

00:34:50.240 --> 00:34:55.040
[Guest]: also, technically, Christianity is not supposed to have caste. But there is a sense of aristocracy

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:59.180
[Guest]: among the old Syrian Christian families were seen as higher caste Christians. And you know,

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:02.840
[Guest]: you need them to come and touch the oil and ghee that goes into a temple only then is

00:35:02.840 --> 00:35:06.560
[Guest]: it purified. In my own ancestral house, every time the ghee etc came from the market, it

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:10.920
[Guest]: was kept outside the kitchen building, a Christian had to be found to touch it to purify it before

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:14.840
[Guest]: it came inside. And it had to be a Syrian Christian, it couldn't be a low caste convert,

00:35:14.840 --> 00:35:18.640
[Guest]: it couldn't be from the LMS or the CMS or one of the later missionary societies. It

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:22.840
[Guest]: couldn't be, you know, anybody else except a Syrian Christian who was considered the

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:27.240
[Guest]: most superior kind of Christian. And within them, they had these these systems in markets

00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:30.880
[Guest]: for everything. So I guess there's a market there for Syrian Christians. Did they actually

00:35:30.880 --> 00:35:34.960
[Guest]: dip their finger in the ghee? No, I think I'm not entirely sure because nobody now remembers

00:35:34.960 --> 00:35:40.080
[Amit Varma]: whether there was a dipping or not. But you're supposed to touch the container at least.

00:35:40.080 --> 00:35:43.560
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting. You know, a little earlier, you were chatting about the common

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:50.040
[Amit Varma]: notion that the British created or at least solidified the caste system. But through your

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:55.920
[Amit Varma]: book, there are also indications on how colonialism may have been something that helped fight

00:35:55.920 --> 00:36:01.160
[Amit Varma]: the caste system. For example, you write about, you have a great chapter about what if the

00:36:01.160 --> 00:36:06.440
[Amit Varma]: British Raj had never been there. And there you point out, quote, ironically, it was British

00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:11.600
[Amit Varma]: rule that allowed low caste voices to emerge at last. It was a missionary education and

00:36:11.600 --> 00:36:17.040
[Amit Varma]: access to Western texts, for instance, that galvanized Jyotiba Phule in his program of

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:23.200
[Amit Varma]: reform. And a little later in the context of Macaulay, you say, quote, nativists resented

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Macaulay, but there were others who embraced this policy. After all, the likes of Jyotirao

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:31.800
[Amit Varma]: Phule, son of a gardener, could never enter Sanskrit schools, but were welcome in English

00:36:31.800 --> 00:36:36.440
[Amit Varma]: institutions. They felt no shame in being painted Macaulay putras when the alternative

00:36:36.440 --> 00:36:40.840
[Amit Varma]: was demeaning drudgery in service of the upper caste, who only appeared less haughty than

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:44.400
[Amit Varma]: Englishmen because they were brown and looked more familiar. Yeah, in fact, this reminds

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:49.360
[Guest]: me of the opening section of Zareer Masani's book on Macaulay. It's a biography. And apparently

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:53.840
[Guest]: even now there are communities of Dalits who celebrate Macaulay's birthday as some sort

00:36:53.840 --> 00:36:58.080
[Guest]: of Jayanti. Because for them, Macaulay is a little bit of a liberator. He's a man who

00:36:58.080 --> 00:37:01.760
[Guest]: finally gives them access to the English language. And Jyotirao Phule, you know, this is a man

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:05.640
[Guest]: who dedicates one of his books, Gulamgiri, to the people of the United States. He reads

00:37:05.640 --> 00:37:09.320
[Guest]: Thomas Paine's writer, Rights of Man, because that's what inspires him. And he reads it

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:14.280
[Guest]: in English. And he's very acutely aware that in the old schools, he has no place. He's

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:20.880
[Guest]: made to feel like a Mali Greengrocer's son. That's what his caste is. And, you know, his

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:25.600
[Guest]: grandfather was a gardener, his father was a greengrocer. So he's made to feel that.

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:29.280
[Guest]: But then English liberates him. This is again why Ambedkar wore a suit because it was easy

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:33.040
[Guest]: for Gandhi to renounce the suit and dress in khadi and all of that because he had the

00:37:33.040 --> 00:37:38.020
[Guest]: privilege. For an Ambedkar, wearing that suit was a sense of identity, was a sense of look.

00:37:38.020 --> 00:37:42.280
[Guest]: My ancestors couldn't wear what they wanted. They were only allowed a loincloth. You, Gandhiji,

00:37:42.280 --> 00:37:45.920
[Guest]: can now discard the suit for the loincloth because he can. My ancestors could only wear

00:37:45.920 --> 00:37:49.200
[Guest]: the loincloth. So now we're going to wear suits. Now we're going to hold those bags.

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:54.080
[Guest]: Mayawati is going to hold her little leather purse because it's a larger principle that

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:59.400
[Guest]: they're trying to project. So yeah, a lot of this British thing, one of the complications

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:04.320
[Guest]: in this whole British equal to bad, Indians equal to good, is that lower caste Indians

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:09.480
[Guest]: did find British rule fairly generous towards them. It created spaces for them, it created

00:38:09.480 --> 00:38:14.200
[Guest]: at least officially, it created a legal system where they could get their grievances addressed.

00:38:14.200 --> 00:38:18.120
[Guest]: A lot of times, you know, a lot of Indian castes would not work in the British army,

00:38:18.120 --> 00:38:21.880
[Guest]: but a lot of Dalit castes would. So, you know, they contributed that way. You know, there's

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:26.240
[Guest]: that famous incident of the battle outside Pune, where, you know, the Mahars even now

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:30.420
[Guest]: celebrate it as a good thing because that's where the British won over the Peshwas people.

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:33.920
[Guest]: And they see it as a good thing because for them, the Peshwas are Brahmins. The Peshwas

00:38:33.920 --> 00:38:37.040
[Guest]: are the ones who insist Mahars should walk around with a broom tied to their waist and

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:41.280
[Guest]: a pot around their neck so that the spit falls into the pot and the broom wipes off their

00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:44.680
[Guest]: footsteps and things like that. And these are people, they supported the British and

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:49.360
[Guest]: they defeated the Peshwas people. So for them, that's a mark of identity. It's a mark of

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:50.360
[Guest]: self-respect.

00:38:50.360 --> 00:38:55.260
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking aloud then, is that one of the reasons that many traditionalists look

00:38:55.260 --> 00:39:02.040
[Amit Varma]: suspiciously at Western modernity and so on, because in a sense, it might bring economic

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:04.680
[Amit Varma]: progress, but it threatens their social standing as well.

00:39:04.680 --> 00:39:09.080
[Guest]: Yeah. So, you know, Periyar has said it, Ambedkar said it, which is that this whole, I mean,

00:39:09.080 --> 00:39:12.760
[Guest]: I'm not agreeing with what they said fully, but their argument was that the whole nationalistic

00:39:12.760 --> 00:39:16.720
[Guest]: movement was about Indian elites wanting to take over from British rulers. So they just

00:39:16.720 --> 00:39:20.160
[Guest]: wanted to slip into the seat that the British had kept warm for them. But they don't want

00:39:20.160 --> 00:39:24.520
[Guest]: to reform anything within the system. They didn't want social upheaval. Gandhi definitely

00:39:24.520 --> 00:39:29.120
[Guest]: didn't want any social upheaval. He wanted peace socially, agitation politically. So

00:39:29.120 --> 00:39:33.040
[Guest]: whereas the low caste leaders all said, you can never have full freedom if you're not

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:37.600
[Guest]: willing to uproot an unjust social order. But unfortunately, you know, that sort of

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:41.280
[Guest]: message is never romantic. And Ambedkar, at the end of the day, you need to be really

00:39:41.280 --> 00:39:45.160
[Guest]: serious to understand his message. He was perhaps the most towering intellectual of

00:39:45.160 --> 00:39:49.880
[Guest]: his generation, far superior to Gandhi and Nehru. But the thing is, his message can't

00:39:49.880 --> 00:39:53.840
[Guest]: be romanticized. It can't be turned into this grand narrative that people find appealing.

00:39:53.840 --> 00:39:59.200
[Guest]: It's a very serious affair. And because of that, the kind of attraction it has for large

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:04.120
[Guest]: masses is lower, because only a certain type of person would prefer that over this grand

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:08.120
[Guest]: notion of the Indian nation and the romance of nationalism and all of that. But the romance

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:12.800
[Guest]: of nationalism conceals a lot of social injustice. It conceals a lot of let's preserve the status

00:40:12.800 --> 00:40:17.400
[Guest]: quo. And that is what the low caste leaders stood up to. Ambedkar, even on the eve of

00:40:17.400 --> 00:40:21.720
[Guest]: independence say about seven years before 1940s, early 40s, was saying things like the

00:40:21.720 --> 00:40:26.440
[Guest]: British don't distinguish between the departure of one tyrant and the right of another tyrant

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:31.440
[Guest]: to start oppressing the people below them. So there's, you know, that sort of messaging

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:36.800
[Guest]: in that as well, which is why even now, at the end of the day, Dalit agitation is particularly

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:41.560
[Guest]: scary for majoritarian groups, because for them that creates or that highlights and holds

00:40:41.560 --> 00:40:46.680
[Guest]: up a mirror to divisions within, which they'd rather avoid and create a pan-Indian Hindu

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:50.840
[Guest]: identity. But the point is, you know, when you say Hindu, that includes so many categories,

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:54.040
[Guest]: and you're not willing to completely give up your sense of privilege within.

00:40:54.040 --> 00:40:59.240
[Amit Varma]: No, I actually agree with Ambedkar and Piyar on this. And even outside the context of caste,

00:40:59.240 --> 00:41:04.480
[Amit Varma]: I would hold that it is true that what we did in 1947 was replaced a set of colonial

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:09.080
[Amit Varma]: rulers with a set of brown skin rulers. And this is true in context, well beyond caste.

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:14.840
[Amit Varma]: And I sort of, you know, I had Ram Guha on my show a few months ago, talking about Gandhi,

00:41:14.840 --> 00:41:17.920
[Amit Varma]: we had a couple of episodes on this. And in the second of those, which I'll link from

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:24.040
[Amit Varma]: the show notes, we spoke about the whole Ambedkar versus Gandhi debates. And I just there feel

00:41:24.040 --> 00:41:28.440
[Amit Varma]: strongly on the side of Ambedkar, because I think while Gandhi paid lip service to caste

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:34.920
[Amit Varma]: upliftment, he also said things like this sentence, which you quote in your book, a

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:40.320
[Amit Varma]: bhangi does for society what a mother does for a baby. And you speak about how Gandhi,

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:45.560
[Amit Varma]: who was so patronizing on this subject, used to talk about the beauty of compromise and

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:51.520
[Amit Varma]: social dynamics between the low who had answers to seek, and the high who had so much to lose.

00:41:51.520 --> 00:41:56.840
[Amit Varma]: These are your words. And, you know, and let's talk about Periyar a bit because the chapter

00:41:56.840 --> 00:42:01.600
[Amit Varma]: was very fascinating. And it made me I haven't read enough about Periyar, you know, so I

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:05.840
[Amit Varma]: instantly skipped to the notes and I to figure out what books I should read. And there's

00:42:05.840 --> 00:42:10.200
[Amit Varma]: another great quote by Periyar on this where he says, if you have to choose between killing

00:42:10.200 --> 00:42:16.480
[Amit Varma]: a Brahmin or a snake, spare the snake. And Periyar was the anti-Gandhi in ways other

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:21.040
[Amit Varma]: than just caste. And I found him to be a really fascinating character. Tell me a bit about

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:25.680
[Guest]: him. He was, you know, he could be very polemical. Obviously, you know, this is a man who smashed

00:42:25.680 --> 00:42:30.520
[Guest]: idols, he used to garland, you know, images of Rama and all with chappals. That was the

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:34.400
[Guest]: kind of thing he did. Again, if Periyar lived 50 years later, he'd probably be lynched,

00:42:34.400 --> 00:42:39.240
[Guest]: but he was an atheist. So when Gandhi renounced sex in his 30s, Periyar got married to a 30

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:43.960
[Guest]: year old in his 70s. Gandhi wore white, Periyar wore black. Gandhi said, you know, Ram Raja

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:48.600
[Guest]: and things like that. Periyar said no atheism. And when and most importantly, you know, Gandhiji

00:42:48.600 --> 00:42:52.840
[Guest]: was all about preserving family and, you know, women in their position. He was a little conservative

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:56.840
[Guest]: in that regard. Whereas Periyar always said women don't look to men to liberate you because

00:42:56.840 --> 00:43:01.720
[Guest]: of you know, when is when have men ever liberated women just like you can't expect a fox or

00:43:01.720 --> 00:43:05.240
[Amit Varma]: something. I'll read the quote out. You've got it in your book, which is have cats ever

00:43:05.240 --> 00:43:11.160
[Amit Varma]: feed rats? Have foxes ever liberated goats or chickens? Have whites ever enriched Indians?

00:43:11.160 --> 00:43:15.760
[Amit Varma]: Have Brahmins ever given non Brahmins justice? We can be confident that women will never

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:20.360
[Guest]: be emancipated by men. Yeah, so you know, the thing is, he's polemical, but the things

00:43:20.360 --> 00:43:23.760
[Guest]: you need people like that, it's a little bit like, you know, if you read Arundhati Roy

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:27.440
[Guest]: today, you don't have to agree with everything she does. But she does a service in the broader

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:32.400
[Guest]: sense, which is that by holding up these very uncomfortable positions by using her influence

00:43:32.400 --> 00:43:36.400
[Guest]: to say certain things, which are not always agreeable, but it holds up a mirror, it makes

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:40.840
[Guest]: us acknowledge that we've got ugly sides to us that we have to recognize and acknowledge.

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:44.160
[Guest]: This is to some extent, that's why I find Periyar fascinating, not because you agree

00:43:44.160 --> 00:43:48.080
[Guest]: with everything he says, but because he asks a lot of uncomfortable questions. At a time

00:43:48.080 --> 00:43:51.280
[Guest]: when it was very easy to blame the British saying you are the villains, and we are these

00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:55.760
[Guest]: victims and we must all rally together. He kept saying hold on, you're not all victims,

00:43:55.760 --> 00:44:00.240
[Guest]: you know, some of you are, you know, privileged, some of you are pretty much in the in, you

00:44:00.240 --> 00:44:03.960
[Guest]: know, in the in cahoots with the British. There are other people who are the real victims

00:44:03.960 --> 00:44:07.960
[Guest]: here and you're not even acknowledging that. So asking awkward questions really fascinates

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:12.360
[Guest]: me because this is a time when the whole momentum is with Gandhiji, the whole momentum is, you

00:44:12.360 --> 00:44:15.680
[Guest]: know, with the freedom struggle and all that. And here's a man essentially being a little

00:44:15.680 --> 00:44:19.640
[Guest]: bit of a party pooper. But it was important that he did it at that time. Because for a

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:23.720
[Guest]: lot of people, you know, that clarified thought that makes us realize that, you know, the

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:27.400
[Guest]: battle is only half won. Throwing out the British is only one part of the beginning

00:44:27.400 --> 00:44:32.680
[Guest]: of a much larger battle. And we haven't won those larger battles even today. And you know,

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:37.360
[Guest]: to that extent, Periyar has value. So even though he's polemical and a little too, you

00:44:37.360 --> 00:44:41.840
[Guest]: know, he can be a rabble rouser even in certain contexts. And I wouldn't say, you know, you

00:44:41.840 --> 00:44:46.360
[Guest]: should go around putting chapals on people's idols. His right to do it is his right. But

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:50.160
[Guest]: you know, that's sort of, it's a little too blunt. And there was a lot of victimization

00:44:50.160 --> 00:44:55.400
[Guest]: of Brahmins as a result of that, which is also not entirely healthy. But as I said,

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:59.320
[Guest]: opening up a mirror is not always easy. So for having done that, he deserves a certain

00:44:59.320 --> 00:45:04.680
[Guest]: amount of interest and acknowledgement. And in fact, speaking of books, you know, Venkatesh

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:08.120
[Guest]: Jalapathy has been working for years and years and years on Periyar and everyone's waiting

00:45:08.120 --> 00:45:13.280
[Guest]: for that book to come out. Because he's, I think, the foremost Periyar scholar. And once

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:18.320
[Guest]: he finishes his book, I think we'll have a really good solid volume on Periyar.

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:21.760
[Amit Varma]: And reading it, I was just thinking, you know, looking back at what happened to guys like

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:26.520
[Amit Varma]: Dabholkar and Pansri. And I was just thinking that, you know, Periyar would be in a bit

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:30.920
[Amit Varma]: of actual trouble today. Like there's this great quote with which you start the book,

00:45:30.920 --> 00:45:36.320
[Amit Varma]: with which I fully agree. Quote, there is no God, there is no God at all. He who created

00:45:36.320 --> 00:45:42.280
[Amit Varma]: God is a fool. He who propagates God is a scoundrel. He who worships God is a barbarian.

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:46.160
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And you know, the fact that he could actually say this. He started every

00:45:46.160 --> 00:45:51.920
[Guest]: public meeting saying that. Gandhiji starting with bhajans and things like that. This is

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:56.080
[Guest]: what Periyar started his public meetings with. So imagine, you know, these two towering figures

00:45:56.080 --> 00:45:59.880
[Guest]: of the time, they're essentially, you know, pretty much contemporaries. And you have one

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:03.800
[Guest]: Gandhi in the North and one anti-Gandhi in the South. And you see in the South, that's

00:46:03.800 --> 00:46:06.720
[Guest]: why even today, if you look at the South, in the South, the freedom struggle was not

00:46:06.720 --> 00:46:12.240
[Guest]: so anti-British. It was also anti-caste, it was for social reform and so on. Whether it's

00:46:12.240 --> 00:46:17.520
[Guest]: Kerala, Tamil Nadu, these were also part of that struggle. It wasn't merely about pushing

00:46:17.520 --> 00:46:21.120
[Guest]: the British out, which you can see that the reflections of that in South Indian society

00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:25.000
[Guest]: even today, you know, women are better off. You know, the caste system exists, there is

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:29.040
[Guest]: still caste violence and so on. But it's not as intense as parts of Northern India, because

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:33.080
[Amit Varma]: these issues were not completely neglected in the South. So how central was Periyar to

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:36.480
[Amit Varma]: this? Because like you said, the South is a peninsula, so it would automatically therefore

00:46:36.480 --> 00:46:40.040
[Guest]: because of those in. The thing is, Periyar, I think at some level was handicapped by language,

00:46:40.040 --> 00:46:44.960
[Guest]: which is that Tamil was his main medium of disseminating his message. So his influence

00:46:44.960 --> 00:46:48.400
[Guest]: was largely in that area. But he did come to Kerala, he's the one who, you know, took

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:53.000
[Guest]: a proactive role in the Vaikam Satyagraha that ended up throwing open roads around temples

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:58.240
[Guest]: to Dalits. So he did come like that, but and famously said that when the Maharaja of Travancore

00:46:58.240 --> 00:47:02.640
[Guest]: refused to allow it, he said, these roads are not the Maharaja's grandfather's property.

00:47:02.640 --> 00:47:06.520
[Guest]: And this is Kerala at that time, the Maharaja of Travancore is the semi-divine figure, nobody

00:47:06.520 --> 00:47:10.280
[Guest]: says anything against him. And Periyar comes and says something like that in a place like

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:15.040
[Guest]: Kerala, which is, which was called by Vivekananda, lunatic asylum of caste, because it's so rigid

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:20.040
[Guest]: and so orthodox. So it's some influence elsewhere, but I think broadly in the Tamil space.

00:47:20.040 --> 00:47:23.920
[Amit Varma]: So for Amits like me, who may not be very aware, tell me a little bit more about his

00:47:23.920 --> 00:47:26.560
[Amit Varma]: influence in Tamil culture and Tamil politics.

00:47:26.560 --> 00:47:32.600
[Guest]: One is this whole rationalist influence, which is that, you know, this anti-Brahminical Hinduism,

00:47:32.600 --> 00:47:36.240
[Guest]: it wasn't and you know, the highlighting of Dravidian culture, etc. Now the funny thing

00:47:36.240 --> 00:47:40.040
[Guest]: is there again, missionaries have a role. They're the ones who first promoted this Dravidian

00:47:40.040 --> 00:47:45.280
[Guest]: identity as very separate notion. And that was picked up into a political concept by

00:47:45.280 --> 00:47:48.720
[Guest]: people like Periyar, where there was a sense of identity and they didn't see why it had

00:47:48.720 --> 00:47:53.360
[Guest]: to merge with or become subsumed by Hindi nationalism or Hindu nationalism or anything.

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:57.560
[Guest]: They were proud to be Tamils. They were not very interested in some of these other messages

00:47:57.560 --> 00:48:03.200
[Guest]: coming from further up north. Then, as I said, his rationalism is very interesting. It obviously

00:48:03.200 --> 00:48:07.120
[Guest]: hasn't lasted in the sense that, you know, people are still devout in temples, etc. still

00:48:07.120 --> 00:48:11.400
[Guest]: important. But if you look at all the Tamil political parties, whether it's a DMK or the

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:16.440
[Guest]: AIDMK, you know, they always pay lip service to this one man because his influence over

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:20.280
[Guest]: local society is so vast that you have to, he's essentially the local Gandhi, you know,

00:48:20.280 --> 00:48:21.280
[Amit Varma]: you can't...

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:24.200
[Amit Varma]: Do they pay lip service to him because he's like a Tamil icon or do they pay lip service

00:48:24.200 --> 00:48:25.640
[Guest]: to him because of his ideas per se?

00:48:25.640 --> 00:48:29.520
[Guest]: I think icon, it's a little bit like Gandhiji, you know, like his ideas, the moment he died,

00:48:29.520 --> 00:48:32.600
[Guest]: all the ideas were put away in a basket and framed and put up in museums.

00:48:32.600 --> 00:48:34.040
[Amit Varma]: And many of them were quite dubious as well.

00:48:34.040 --> 00:48:37.800
[Guest]: Yeah, they were pretty dubious. And, you know, I have this essay saying, what if Gandhi had

00:48:37.800 --> 00:48:40.840
[Guest]: lived? And the whole point is that if he had actually lived, he would have become a headache

00:48:40.840 --> 00:48:44.800
[Guest]: for Nehru, most likely. And all the other people in power, because suddenly you're in

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:48.840
[Guest]: power. It's very easy to say things when you're not in power. But once you're, you know, you

00:48:48.840 --> 00:48:52.560
[Guest]: can have romantic notions of the nation, freedom and all of that when you're not in power.

00:48:52.560 --> 00:48:56.520
[Guest]: When you're in power, there's something called a budget, there's the economy, there are social

00:48:56.520 --> 00:49:00.160
[Guest]: rival competing claims that need to be balanced. There's industrialists on one side, labor

00:49:00.160 --> 00:49:03.720
[Guest]: on the other side, which means there's going to be compromise. At that time, a Gandhiji

00:49:03.720 --> 00:49:07.760
[Guest]: with his pious principles sitting above this whole edifice, you know, saying things would

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:11.680
[Guest]: have been an inconvenience, I suspect, for Nehru. So, you know, it's a little bit like

00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:15.360
[Guest]: that where Periyar also, some of the things he did, they would never repeat today, it

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:19.240
[Guest]: would be impossible. But, you know, you pay lip service, you always say that he's a great

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:23.600
[Guest]: Tamil icon. And therefore, for that reason, give Periyar a certain amount of respect.

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:28.160
[Amit Varma]: I was reading the chapter on him with great jealousy, because you cite the title of one

00:49:28.160 --> 00:49:32.640
[Amit Varma]: of his op-eds, which is honeymoon in the Hindu zoo. And I, you know, I write a column for

00:49:32.640 --> 00:49:37.600
[Amit Varma]: the Times of India. And man, if I suggested that as a headline, there is no way to pass.

00:49:37.600 --> 00:49:43.520
[Amit Varma]: Today, it simply wouldn't fly from this very serious subject of caste. And while staying

00:49:43.520 --> 00:49:47.920
[Amit Varma]: on the serious subject of caste, let's also go to some blood and violence. You've got

00:49:47.920 --> 00:49:52.600
[Guest]: this great chapter, which I was actually half afraid that now, by this time in the conversation,

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:57.600
[Amit Varma]: people would assume the entire book is only about caste, which it isn't at all. It's just

00:49:57.600 --> 00:50:00.880
[Amit Varma]: one of the themes that I picked up on, but it's quite incidental. It's, it's, there's

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:07.720
[Amit Varma]: nothing sort of polemical in your, your stories are basically bloodshed and violence, when

00:50:07.720 --> 00:50:12.680
[Amit Varma]: I say that in a good way. So there's this great chapter you have called the bloody monsoon

00:50:12.680 --> 00:50:18.560
[Amit Varma]: of Vellore. And caste creeps into this as well. Tell me a little bit about the bloody

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:19.560
[Guest]: monsoon of Vellore.

00:50:19.560 --> 00:50:23.000
[Guest]: So this is in the early 19th century, you know, there's this quest in India always to

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:26.960
[Guest]: find the first war against the British or the first war of independence. It's futile.

00:50:26.960 --> 00:50:29.600
[Guest]: I mean, the further back you go, there's always someone or the other fighting the British

00:50:29.600 --> 00:50:33.440
[Guest]: somewhere or the other. So there are different, each state has one version of when the first

00:50:33.440 --> 00:50:37.240
[Guest]: agitation against the British took place. In Vellore, we're in the early 19th century,

00:50:37.240 --> 00:50:40.960
[Guest]: where, you know, Tipu's family is imprisoned in Vellore Fort. There's the British were

00:50:40.960 --> 00:50:47.200
[Guest]: there as the local garrison. And well before 1857, about 45 years before 1857, what they

00:50:47.200 --> 00:50:51.400
[Guest]: do is they introduce new uniforms. So they tell the men that you're all British soldiers,

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:54.840
[Guest]: your mustaches need to be standardized, your beards need to be standardized, your turban

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:59.000
[Guest]: is going to be standardized, all of that, which in India, I mean, it's very convenient

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:03.480
[Guest]: to look at this as a matter of costume. But in India, costume signifies custom, it signifies

00:51:03.480 --> 00:51:08.040
[Guest]: caste. One of the things about why clothes were regulated so much was because back in

00:51:08.040 --> 00:51:11.160
[Guest]: the day, how do you tell a person's caste? You should be able to tell at one glance what

00:51:11.160 --> 00:51:14.520
[Guest]: ornaments they're wearing, what their hairstyle is, you know, in Kerala, for example, the

00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:18.480
[Guest]: munda or the variant of the lungi that we wear, if it's above the knee or lower caste,

00:51:18.480 --> 00:51:23.480
[Guest]: below the knees, higher caste. So you can tell based simply on that much of an indicator.

00:51:23.480 --> 00:51:27.040
[Guest]: Certain castes were allowed certain kinds of jewellery, certain castes were not. So

00:51:27.040 --> 00:51:30.640
[Guest]: in Vellore also, when different soldiers from different castes were suddenly told that they

00:51:30.640 --> 00:51:34.120
[Guest]: should have the same moustache, and they should have the same hat, and things like that, they

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:37.160
[Guest]: were a little upset, because for them, it looked like they were being Christianized,

00:51:37.160 --> 00:51:41.920
[Guest]: they were being secretly converted without realizing and they were lampooned by a lot

00:51:41.920 --> 00:51:45.600
[Guest]: of people. And the funny thing is, the British thought the whole rebellion or the mutiny

00:51:45.600 --> 00:51:51.200
[Guest]: was provoked by Tipu's family. In reality, it wasn't. Some of Tipu's family's attendants

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:55.080
[Guest]: used to, you know, sort of giggle at these people saying you're all essentially British,

00:51:55.080 --> 00:51:59.960
[Guest]: behaving like British chelas, topi walas, and you're losing your, your caste identity

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:04.600
[Guest]: and your original identity. But beyond that, they were not very, very, you know, involved

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:08.240
[Guest]: in it. But the British were so embarrassed that it was something as silly as costume

00:52:08.240 --> 00:52:11.760
[Guest]: and moustaches that caused this mutiny that they eventually determined that it had to

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:15.400
[Guest]: be Tipu's family. And you know, Tipu's family was penalized, and they were all sent off

00:52:15.400 --> 00:52:20.040
[Guest]: to Calcutta and so on. But it wasn't actually them, it was simply the fact that they were

00:52:20.040 --> 00:52:25.200
[Amit Varma]: trying to meddle with caste. And it's quite funny the way the British reacted and the

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:29.680
[Amit Varma]: way they were initially like, there's a great quote by here on where an officer later said

00:52:29.680 --> 00:52:34.240
[Amit Varma]: that they couldn't believe what happened because quote, the natives of Hindustan are meek and

00:52:34.240 --> 00:52:38.800
[Amit Varma]: submissive beyond any other example in national character, stop quote. So they're like, what

00:52:38.800 --> 00:52:44.240
[Guest]: is the uniform and the rebel? This, I think, is from a parliamentary committee report that

00:52:44.240 --> 00:52:48.280
[Guest]: inquired into this afterwards. And remember, this is also in those days, communication

00:52:48.280 --> 00:52:52.240
[Guest]: is very slow, right? So by the time the rebellions happen, and it happened, ended everything,

00:52:52.240 --> 00:52:55.320
[Guest]: it's only months later that London hears the news. And London, of course, is in a panic

00:52:55.320 --> 00:52:57.920
[Guest]: because they don't know what's happened since and they know six months have passed, but

00:52:57.920 --> 00:53:01.320
[Guest]: they have no idea whether the rebellions, you know, been put down, what's happening,

00:53:01.320 --> 00:53:06.760
[Guest]: etc. So there's lots of like, you know, miscommunication and all of that also happening. But yeah,

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:11.640
[Guest]: it's quite funny that the British even changing, you know, uniforms and changing people's facial

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:16.440
[Guest]: hair could provoke such violence because people took these things very seriously.

00:53:16.440 --> 00:53:21.680
[Amit Varma]: And I love this line also, quote, retribution was swift that this is when the British retake

00:53:21.680 --> 00:53:27.560
[Amit Varma]: the fort. Quote, retribution was swift of the 1500 Indian troops present, about 400

00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:32.640
[Amit Varma]: were killed immediately, some of them blown out of cannons, presumably to transmit the

00:53:32.640 --> 00:53:36.840
[Amit Varma]: message far and wide. Stop good. This is fantastic. How do you blow someone out of a cannon?

00:53:36.840 --> 00:53:39.920
[Guest]: Oh, you hit it with the gunpowder or whatever, tie them on it. And then you know, that's

00:53:39.920 --> 00:53:42.600
[Guest]: how you blow them out. It's also supposed to be very painless because they don't really

00:53:42.600 --> 00:53:47.240
[Amit Varma]: feel it. It's so quick. But how do you know they don't feel it? No, I mean, it was considered

00:53:47.240 --> 00:53:52.400
[Guest]: a merciful way of execution as late as the 1870s. They were still doing it. So you know,

00:53:52.400 --> 00:53:55.960
[Guest]: this was considered a merciful way of execution because for the person it was quick. Before

00:53:55.960 --> 00:54:00.720
[Guest]: they knew it, they were dead. But for the people witnessing, it was such horror that

00:54:00.720 --> 00:54:05.040
[Amit Varma]: it, you know, made the message very clear. The body gets blown into pieces. Like imagine,

00:54:05.040 --> 00:54:09.840
[Guest]: you know, people's flesh landing on different, you know, parts of that that general area.

00:54:09.840 --> 00:54:14.880
[Amit Varma]: It was just disgusting, very colorful. Like if you want to make a web series, kindly incorporate

00:54:14.880 --> 00:54:19.680
[Amit Varma]: this. Yeah. And for countries which debate like which have capital punishment and which

00:54:19.680 --> 00:54:24.640
