[Unknown]: Tripathi is joined by film director Vikram Fadnis. He talks about how he started his

00:56:23.360 --> 00:56:26.880
[Unknown]: journey from being a fashion designer to becoming a movie director and his upcoming Marathi

00:56:26.880 --> 00:56:31.240
[Unknown]: movie Smile Please. Also, our host Tripathi plays an important part in this movie. On

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:35.680
[Unknown]: Not Just Dhansak, Parzen talks to chef Virat Patel about Parsi fusion food. They discuss

00:56:35.680 --> 00:56:39.600
[Unknown]: innovation versus traditional food in the Parsi food circles. On Puliyabazi, Pranayil

00:56:39.600 --> 00:56:43.160
[Unknown]: Saurabh talks with investor and trader Harsh Vohra to better understand the tussle between

00:56:43.160 --> 00:56:50.200
[Unknown]: the Reserve Bank of India and the Indian government. And with that, let's continue with your show.

00:56:50.200 --> 00:56:53.200
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the Scene and the Unseen. I'm chatting with the historian Manu Pillay

00:56:53.200 --> 00:56:58.960
[Amit Varma]: about his book The Courtesan, The Mahatma and the Italian Brahman. And one of your early

00:56:58.960 --> 00:57:03.800
[Amit Varma]: stories is very fascinating. It's titled The Tale of Two Shakuntalas. Well, there weren't

00:57:03.800 --> 00:57:07.360
[Amit Varma]: actually two Shakuntalas. There was one and at the same time, there were kind of two.

00:57:07.360 --> 00:57:11.080
[Guest]: Tell me a little bit about that. So you know, there is what is our general knowledge of

00:57:11.080 --> 00:57:14.920
[Guest]: Shakuntala. She's this woman, there's this king, he departs, you know, they have this

00:57:14.920 --> 00:57:19.040
[Guest]: wonderful union and they're in love or whatever. Then he departs giving her a ring saying this,

00:57:19.040 --> 00:57:24.360
[Guest]: you know, it's a token that he's given her. And then, you know, one day sage comes and

00:57:24.360 --> 00:57:27.960
[Guest]: she's a little distracted because she's lost her heads in the clouds and all of that. So

00:57:27.960 --> 00:57:31.480
[Guest]: saint curses her saying that the man who you're thinking about, he will forget you. But then

00:57:31.480 --> 00:57:35.320
[Guest]: everyone runs to the saint and says, Oh my God, you know, poor girl, whatever, whatever.

00:57:35.320 --> 00:57:39.160
[Guest]: So he says, okay, fine. When you present the ring, he will remember you. Now on the way

00:57:39.160 --> 00:57:44.480
[Guest]: to the king's court later and she's pregnant, the ring gets lost. And then when she gets

00:57:44.480 --> 00:57:49.280
[Guest]: there, the king doesn't recognize her and she feels insulted and she leaves. And later

00:57:49.280 --> 00:57:53.720
[Guest]: a fish turns out has swallowed the ring and the fish is brought, the ring is then finally

00:57:53.720 --> 00:57:57.160
[Guest]: it ends up in court. And that's when the king realizes and all of that. And he goes on a

00:57:57.160 --> 00:58:01.520
[Guest]: quest and finds Shakuntala again and finds his son and all of that years later. So son's

00:58:01.520 --> 00:58:06.720
[Guest]: already grown up by then. But the funny thing is this is Kalidasa Shakuntala. This is the

00:58:06.720 --> 00:58:11.080
[Guest]: popular Shakuntala that the British also popularized. William Jones, for example, translated this

00:58:11.080 --> 00:58:15.400
[Guest]: Shakuntala into his play Sakuntala or the fatal ring. You know, and this is the one

00:58:15.400 --> 00:58:21.840
[Guest]: that was staged in Europe and all of that. So this is the one that we've largely consumed

00:58:21.840 --> 00:58:26.240
[Guest]: over the last few generations because people think this is the original story. But the

00:58:26.240 --> 00:58:30.280
[Guest]: interesting thing is that the original Shakuntala story appears in the epics in the Mahabharata,

00:58:30.280 --> 00:58:33.640
[Guest]: but it's very different. It's very simple. Dushyanta comes, he's in the middle of a hunt,

00:58:33.640 --> 00:58:37.600
[Guest]: lands in this hermitage and he says, who's here? And there's no servants. She's not coy

00:58:37.600 --> 00:58:41.840
[Guest]: or shy. Shakuntala comes out and introduces herself and starts talking. And he says, oh,

00:58:41.840 --> 00:58:46.760
[Guest]: who's this woman with the wonderful ties and this baksam lady and all of that. And he says

00:58:46.760 --> 00:58:51.360
[Amit Varma]: Mani Brahmins is one of the themes of your book. This is the Kshatriya king by the way.

00:58:51.360 --> 00:58:56.400
[Guest]: But this man essentially says, lie with me, oh beautiful one and so on. And she, you know,

00:58:56.400 --> 00:59:00.000
[Guest]: first she says, oh, well, should I, should I not? Then she finally says, okay, why not?

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.760
[Guest]: And there's this convenient form of marriage called Gandharva Vivaha where it makes up

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:08.960
[Guest]: for lack of ritual and patience because you can simply go ahead and do what you want and

00:59:08.960 --> 00:59:13.800
[Guest]: pretend that it was done and that the marriage is ready. So she says, fine, but the son born

00:59:13.800 --> 00:59:19.080
[Guest]: from this should be king. So she, to begin with, imposes a condition. So she's not a

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:24.600
[Guest]: completely innocent, you know, helpless woman who won't even talk. She doesn't even talk.

00:59:24.600 --> 00:59:28.640
[Guest]: She's such a shy, docile woman. Whereas this Shakuntala is pretty straightforward. She's

00:59:28.640 --> 00:59:33.400
[Guest]: got agency. She's got agency. Yeah. So she says, my son must be ruler. He agrees. They

00:59:33.400 --> 00:59:37.880
[Guest]: consummate the thing and then he goes away. Now the funny thing is in this Shakuntala,

00:59:37.880 --> 00:59:42.320
[Guest]: her pregnancy lasts 36 months. She's pregnant for three years. Then finally she's had the

00:59:42.320 --> 00:59:46.120
[Guest]: son and she takes him to court. And there she, you know, says, look, I'll keep your

00:59:46.120 --> 00:59:50.480
[Guest]: word now. I've brought your son to you. This must be your heir. And the funny thing is

00:59:50.480 --> 00:59:54.560
[Guest]: here, there's no ring. The ring as it happens is inspired by a Buddhist story that's completely

00:59:54.560 --> 00:59:58.000
[Guest]: different and Kalidas borrows from there and a bunch of others also borrow from there.

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:02.160
[Guest]: In the original story, there's no ring. Tushant has deliberately lied because what he says

01:00:02.160 --> 01:00:05.920
[Guest]: is, you know, there are birds that lay their eggs in other birds nests. So if I, in my

01:00:05.920 --> 01:00:09.960
[Guest]: court, if I openly accept the strange woman coming here with a child that this is my child,

01:00:09.960 --> 01:00:13.600
[Guest]: what would my people think of me? So he says, you know, no, no, no, no, no. He starts insulting

01:00:13.600 --> 01:00:17.640
[Guest]: her. But again, she doesn't weep or whatever. She's angry. She says that, you know, my birth

01:00:17.640 --> 01:00:22.000
[Guest]: is higher than yours and whether or not you acknowledge, you know, you rule the earth.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:26.120
[Guest]: I, you know, fly by, fly in the skies. And whether or not you acknowledge your son, he's

01:00:26.120 --> 01:00:30.200
[Guest]: going to be an even greater king than you are. That's when there's this divine voice

01:00:30.200 --> 01:00:34.120
[Guest]: that says, oh, no, she is speaking the truth. And then the king says, yes, yes, yes, you

01:00:34.120 --> 01:00:37.600
[Guest]: are speaking the truth. I was just testing you and things like that. So it's funny that,

01:00:37.600 --> 01:00:41.920
[Guest]: you know, there's still that patriarchal angle to it. But this Shakuntala is definitely not

01:00:41.920 --> 01:00:46.320
[Guest]: a shy Shakuntala. She has no issues speaking to men. She doesn't need her maids in attendance

01:00:46.320 --> 01:00:51.120
[Guest]: to talk for her. She doesn't. There's no curse that takes the story outside human action

01:00:51.120 --> 01:00:55.920
[Guest]: into divine or, you know, fate, fate, the levels of fate. It's about humans, human beings

01:00:55.920 --> 01:01:00.120
[Guest]: and their choices and their actions. And Tushant deliberately lies and Shakuntala deliberately

01:01:00.120 --> 01:01:04.240
[Guest]: stands up for herself. That's the difference between the two stories and conveniently we've

01:01:04.240 --> 01:01:08.680
[Guest]: forgotten the original Shakuntala. And we've popularized this other Shakuntala who's now

01:01:08.680 --> 01:01:14.600
[Guest]: this ideal of womanhood and Indian wifely conduct and all of that where she's sweet

01:01:14.600 --> 01:01:17.080
[Amit Varma]: and doesn't say anything and you know, all of that.

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:22.520
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of recasting of strong independent women into how you would like to see them

01:01:22.520 --> 01:01:27.760
[Amit Varma]: seems common. Like, you have many chapters on women in your book, you talk about how

01:01:27.760 --> 01:01:33.120
[Amit Varma]: Meenakshi, for example, was recast from a warrior queen to a loving goddess, because

01:01:33.120 --> 01:01:38.120
[Amit Varma]: that's more palatable, I suppose, in a patriarchal society. You also talk about Meerabai, who

01:01:38.120 --> 01:01:42.320
[Amit Varma]: was recast as, you know, an icon of feminine God loving devotion.

01:01:42.320 --> 01:01:47.240
[Guest]: Meera has become this big Krishna Bhakta, but we forget the fact that she stood up to

01:01:47.240 --> 01:01:51.080
[Guest]: what Rajput notions of widows honour was, she said, No, you know, I'm going to meet

01:01:51.080 --> 01:01:54.880
[Guest]: men, I'm going to meet these other devotees, I have no issues interacting with other men.

01:01:54.880 --> 01:01:59.400
[Guest]: And so long as I'm clear within my mind, what my interest is, which is God, I don't see

01:01:59.400 --> 01:02:02.800
[Guest]: why you should have issues with who I meet and what sages I'm hanging out with and all

01:02:02.800 --> 01:02:03.800
[Guest]: of that.

01:02:03.800 --> 01:02:07.520
[Guest]: So but then we conveniently forget that aspect, we conveniently forget the way she stands

01:02:07.520 --> 01:02:11.160
[Guest]: up to her family, she stands up to her brother in law, who's trying to sort of, you know,

01:02:11.160 --> 01:02:15.360
[Guest]: make her live in this this typical life of a widow, the prescribed life that is meant

01:02:15.360 --> 01:02:18.080
[Guest]: for a widow who's not committed sati, by the way.

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:22.960
[Guest]: And that is all forgotten. Instead, she's usually presented as this Krishna Bhakta.

01:02:22.960 --> 01:02:26.600
[Guest]: Her devotion to God is one thing because you want that in your wives and daughters, but

01:02:26.600 --> 01:02:30.240
[Guest]: you don't want your wives and daughters to question you, to question patriarchal institutions,

01:02:30.240 --> 01:02:34.280
[Guest]: to have the freedom to meet who they want to articulate ideas that they like, and to

01:02:34.280 --> 01:02:35.280
[Guest]: move around freely.

01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:39.840
[Guest]: So that, you know, we always pick and choose very cleverly, where even these inconvenient

01:02:39.840 --> 01:02:44.240
[Guest]: women, we end up choosing something that is relatively less inconvenient and making that

01:02:44.240 --> 01:02:47.840
[Guest]: the main thing about them, when in reality, they had so many other layers and so much

01:02:47.840 --> 01:02:49.600
[Amit Varma]: more texture to their personalities.

01:02:49.600 --> 01:02:53.720
[Guest]: And in your chapter on Mirabai, you in fact contrast her with Padmavati, the possibly

01:02:53.720 --> 01:02:59.120
[Amit Varma]: fictional Padmavati, who is, you know, who fits that notion of a woman who will, you

01:02:59.120 --> 01:03:03.160
[Amit Varma]: know, commit sati rather than whatever, and who doesn't really have a voice of her own

01:03:03.160 --> 01:03:04.160
[Amit Varma]: in that sense.

01:03:04.160 --> 01:03:08.400
[Guest]: And that's interesting, right? Like Mirabai existed and Padmavati is, as you said, very

01:03:08.400 --> 01:03:14.520
[Guest]: likely fictional, but they had to create that Padmavati to hold up that ideal of womanhood.

01:03:14.520 --> 01:03:20.120
[Amit Varma]: And even Mirabai, you have to recast her to, you know, be comfortable with sort of what

01:03:20.120 --> 01:03:21.800
[Amit Varma]: she was.

01:03:21.800 --> 01:03:25.760
[Amit Varma]: Another really fascinating chapter in your book, a pretty short chapter is called The

01:03:25.760 --> 01:03:31.640
[Amit Varma]: Lost Begum of Ahmednagar, which is about this remarkable woman called Khunza Humayun.

01:03:31.640 --> 01:03:33.040
[Amit Varma]: And she's really extraordinary.

01:03:33.040 --> 01:03:37.960
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, you know, her daughter Chand Bibi is remembered more, Chand Bibi also makes

01:03:37.960 --> 01:03:42.840
[Amit Varma]: an appearance in Rebel Sultans, your earlier book, which we discussed, I think we discussed

01:03:42.840 --> 01:03:44.440
[Amit Varma]: in the last episode.

01:03:44.440 --> 01:03:49.200
[Amit Varma]: But people don't speak so often of Khunza Humayun and you do, of course, in your great

01:03:49.200 --> 01:03:50.200
[Amit Varma]: chapter.

01:03:50.200 --> 01:03:51.200
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about it.

01:03:51.200 --> 01:03:54.040
[Guest]: So the funny thing is, you know, Khunza was a footnote, initially, there's a paragraph

01:03:54.040 --> 01:03:57.320
[Guest]: dedicated to her in my second book, and my editor said, look, this is a little out of

01:03:57.320 --> 01:03:58.320
[Guest]: the way.

01:03:58.320 --> 01:03:59.880
[Guest]: So can we, you know, get rid of this bit.

01:03:59.880 --> 01:04:02.440
[Guest]: So she ends up being mentioned in passing in the footnote.

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:04.680
[Guest]: She's not mentioned by name in the main text, but she appears in the footnote.

01:04:04.680 --> 01:04:08.800
[Guest]: But I always thought, you know, there's so much more to this lady, because she, you know,

01:04:08.800 --> 01:04:13.600
[Guest]: we have this habit of glorifying women if they're either masculine in the way they go

01:04:13.600 --> 01:04:14.600
[Guest]: down.

01:04:14.600 --> 01:04:17.520
[Guest]: For example, Rani Lakshmibai of Jhansi, you know, she dies fighting, therefore, there's

01:04:17.520 --> 01:04:20.400
[Guest]: some valor attached to her, or they have to be big bhakti people.

01:04:20.400 --> 01:04:23.800
[Guest]: And therefore, there's another kind of virtue attached to them, or if you die with sati

01:04:23.800 --> 01:04:27.760
[Guest]: or something, something dramatically, you know, tragic has to happen with you, for you

01:04:27.760 --> 01:04:28.760
[Guest]: to be respected.

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:33.300
[Guest]: Khunza, on the other hand, she has naked ambition, you know, this is a woman whose husband is

01:04:33.300 --> 01:04:37.800
[Guest]: deeply in love with her, he, you know, he and she, she clearly was advising him in matters

01:04:37.800 --> 01:04:38.800
[Guest]: of state, etc.

01:04:38.800 --> 01:04:45.440
[Guest]: She dies in 1565, soon after defeating Vijayanagar and, you know, breaking that empire for good.

01:04:45.440 --> 01:04:49.360
[Guest]: She becomes regent for their son, but she's very interested in power herself.

01:04:49.360 --> 01:04:52.640
[Guest]: So the thing is, there are several attempts by noblemen to get rid of this, this woman

01:04:52.640 --> 01:04:56.280
[Guest]: because they find her meddlesome and problematic, but she won't give up that easily.

01:04:56.280 --> 01:04:59.600
[Guest]: And finally, they succeed and they go and get her son to push her out.

01:04:59.600 --> 01:05:02.840
[Guest]: And the funny thing is, because she doesn't go down fighting valorously, like her daughter

01:05:02.840 --> 01:05:07.760
[Guest]: Chang Bibi, who dies, you know, in the midst of the Mughal siege and so on, she's not remembered.

01:05:07.760 --> 01:05:14.040
[Guest]: She rots away in jail, and her son is so hateful of her ambition and her general interest in

01:05:14.040 --> 01:05:17.880
[Guest]: governing and administration, that not only does he wipe her out of records, he even paints

01:05:17.880 --> 01:05:22.000
[Guest]: her out of miniature paintings, paintings that showed her with her late husband, the

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.820
[Guest]: boy's father, you know, in his lap, sitting next to him, etc.

01:05:24.820 --> 01:05:28.160
[Guest]: You can see these miniature paintings where the Nizam Shah of Ahmednagar, the husband

01:05:28.160 --> 01:05:31.360
[Guest]: is still intact, and there are maids and servants, etc. in the background.

01:05:31.360 --> 01:05:32.680
[Guest]: But next to him, you'll see this blob.

01:05:32.680 --> 01:05:36.880
[Guest]: The blob is what what used to be Khunza Umayyad, but which her son had painted over, because

01:05:36.880 --> 01:05:38.920
[Guest]: he's completely unhappy with this lady.

01:05:38.920 --> 01:05:41.960
[Guest]: And because as I said, she didn't die at the end of a sword, there's nobody to even sing

01:05:41.960 --> 01:05:45.000
[Guest]: her songs of romantic songs about her.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:49.520
[Guest]: She was a woman who, you know, represented ambition as a man would have it.

01:05:49.520 --> 01:05:50.680
[Guest]: And that was taboo.

01:05:50.680 --> 01:05:53.820
[Guest]: So there was no, no glory for her, no poets for her.

01:05:53.820 --> 01:05:55.600
[Amit Varma]: She just faded away.

01:05:55.600 --> 01:06:01.680
[Amit Varma]: And there's a little interesting nugget in your chapter on her, on how she may have been

01:06:01.680 --> 01:06:06.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of a cause of the war against Vijayanagar, you know, because her husband gets offended,

01:06:06.840 --> 01:06:11.920
[Amit Varma]: when there's an inflammatory letter sent from the Raya of Vijayanagar, where besides demanding

01:06:11.920 --> 01:06:16.960
[Amit Varma]: tribute, he also demands along with diamonds and rubies, the anklets of the Begum.

01:06:16.960 --> 01:06:19.240
[Guest]: Yeah, this is obviously stirs his patriarchy.

01:06:19.240 --> 01:06:23.280
[Guest]: This is based on one account, and which is a sort of poetic account, it may not really

01:06:23.280 --> 01:06:24.280
[Guest]: have happened that way.

01:06:24.280 --> 01:06:27.360
[Guest]: But the thing is, what's interesting is, if you read one of Sanjay Rizwan Brahmanyam's

01:06:27.360 --> 01:06:31.800
[Guest]: essays, and it's a chapter in one of his books, also, there's a thing called Kotli insults.

01:06:31.800 --> 01:06:35.520
[Guest]: Even kings when they exchanged insults, it was done with great style.

01:06:35.520 --> 01:06:38.920
[Guest]: So Vijayanagar sends this message saying, send me so many rubies and send me so many

01:06:38.920 --> 01:06:39.920
[Guest]: diamonds, etc.

01:06:39.920 --> 01:06:43.240
[Guest]: But they also want the Begum's anklets because they're making a point.

01:06:43.240 --> 01:06:47.000
[Guest]: And it's not like the Deccan Sultans were any less, even they used to know how to how

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:48.000
[Guest]: to retaliate.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:53.280
[Guest]: There was this time in my second book where, you know, one of the Bhamani Sultans, there's

01:06:53.280 --> 01:06:57.640
[Guest]: this beautiful goldsmith's daughter in Raichur, and the Raya of Vijayanagar wants her.

01:06:57.640 --> 01:07:01.160
[Guest]: And he comes and sort of seizes her and this man says, No, no, you can't have her.

01:07:01.160 --> 01:07:05.000
[Guest]: And then he goes and there's a big war, he not only you know, he not only defeats Vijayanagar,

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:08.840
[Guest]: but poor girl ends up becoming married to the Sultan's son, who, as we were discussing

01:07:08.840 --> 01:07:12.920
[Guest]: earlier, gets blinded and you know, spends the rest of his life in oblivion.

01:07:12.920 --> 01:07:16.920
[Guest]: So there's a lot of this Kotli insult tradition also going back and forth.

01:07:16.920 --> 01:07:20.440
[Guest]: And this is one of those instances where Kunza Humayun's anklets became one of the things

01:07:20.440 --> 01:07:22.600
[Guest]: that riled up her husband.

01:07:22.600 --> 01:07:25.440
[Guest]: But for all you know, it was just an excuse to go to war.

01:07:25.440 --> 01:07:30.240
[Guest]: The war was anyway coming up, regardless of whether or not the Begum's anklets were involved.

01:07:30.240 --> 01:07:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And I wonder how these guys would have done in the time of Twitter.

01:07:33.600 --> 01:07:36.960
[Amit Varma]: There's a great chapter in your book, which I really enjoyed as a woman who had no reason

01:07:36.960 --> 01:07:37.960
[Amit Varma]: for shame.

01:07:37.960 --> 01:07:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about Muddu Pallani.

01:07:40.240 --> 01:07:41.240
[Guest]: Is that the correct?

01:07:41.240 --> 01:07:42.240
[Guest]: Muddu Pallani.

01:07:42.240 --> 01:07:45.000
[Guest]: This is you know, one of those 18th century courtesans.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:47.840
[Guest]: One of the things is, you know, one of the titles, the title is courtesan, the Mahatma

01:07:47.840 --> 01:07:48.840
[Guest]: and the Italian Brahmin.

01:07:48.840 --> 01:07:52.860
[Guest]: The Italian Brahmin, there's only one, which is which we've already discussed the Mahatma,

01:07:52.860 --> 01:07:56.320
[Guest]: you would think it's Mahatma Gandhi, but Phule was also a Mahatma, you know, it's open to

01:07:56.320 --> 01:07:58.360
[Guest]: interpretation which Mahatma you're talking about.

01:07:58.360 --> 01:08:03.040
[Guest]: But the courtesan, there are several courtesans, there's, you know, the so called Bhagmati after

01:08:03.040 --> 01:08:06.600
[Guest]: whom Hyderabad is named, but she, for all you know, never existed, and was always a

01:08:06.600 --> 01:08:09.160
[Guest]: figment of somebody's imagination.

01:08:09.160 --> 01:08:14.080
[Guest]: There's Begum Samru, who in the late 18th century, early 19th century was equally ally

01:08:14.080 --> 01:08:17.840
[Guest]: of the British and protector of the Mughal Emperor, which is she began as a dancing girl

01:08:17.840 --> 01:08:20.440
[Guest]: and was married to all these foreigners.

01:08:20.440 --> 01:08:25.920
[Guest]: There's Muddu Pallani in the 18th century, who wrote erotica, and famously this work

01:08:25.920 --> 01:08:31.160
[Guest]: called Radhika Santhonam, where, you know, what's interesting is there is, I referred

01:08:31.160 --> 01:08:35.360
[Guest]: to Kshetra earlier, where, you know, God is treated as a customer on his way to his courtesan.

01:08:35.360 --> 01:08:39.520
[Guest]: And there is a lot of eroticism, there is sensuousness, one of the Nayaka rulers in

01:08:39.520 --> 01:08:44.640
[Guest]: during the Nayaka period in Tamil Nadu, one of his wives, you know, she talks about, there's

01:08:44.640 --> 01:08:48.920
[Guest]: a lot of sexual energy that's, being a king meant you had to have a lot of sexual energy.

01:08:48.920 --> 01:08:53.000
[Guest]: Even one of the Nayakas when he was praised by his son, you know, in a work the son composed,

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:56.400
[Guest]: he talks about how many women his father had around him and seduced and he made love to

01:08:56.400 --> 01:08:58.200
[Guest]: an astonishing number of women and things like that.

01:08:58.200 --> 01:09:00.920
[Guest]: So that was part of manly vigor and so on.

01:09:00.920 --> 01:09:04.880
[Guest]: But what's interesting with Muddu Palani is, here it's a woman's sexual desire that becomes

01:09:04.880 --> 01:09:05.880
[Guest]: central.

01:09:05.880 --> 01:09:10.080
[Guest]: The theme is that, you know, Radha is getting her niece Ila married to Krishna.

01:09:10.080 --> 01:09:13.080
[Guest]: And she's, you know, prepared her and she's telling her, you know, you must bear his cloying

01:09:13.080 --> 01:09:16.880
[Guest]: and this is how love, this is how you make love to somebody and all of that.

01:09:16.880 --> 01:09:20.320
[Guest]: And then she takes Ila to the bedchamber and delivers her there.

01:09:20.320 --> 01:09:23.920
[Guest]: And then when Radha comes back to her own room, she's completely consumed by jealousy

01:09:23.920 --> 01:09:28.120
[Guest]: because she thinks, oh, this woman with a body as soft as bananas is going to sort of

01:09:28.120 --> 01:09:31.160
[Guest]: replace me in Krishna's mind and heart.

01:09:31.160 --> 01:09:33.840
[Guest]: And the rest of the thing is about how Krishna appeases her.

01:09:33.840 --> 01:09:39.120
[Guest]: But it's not just that Radha is jealous about the new woman, she also demands and extracts

01:09:39.120 --> 01:09:42.600
[Guest]: from Krishna physical satisfaction.

01:09:42.600 --> 01:09:45.400
[Guest]: So there's this one time where, you know, Krishna complains that, you know, even if

01:09:45.400 --> 01:09:48.960
[Guest]: I tell her I'm not in a mood, she jumps on bed and starts the game of love.

01:09:48.960 --> 01:09:52.000
[Guest]: And he's almost frustrated by it because he can't quite satisfy the lady because she's

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:53.840
[Guest]: quite determined in that sense.

01:09:53.840 --> 01:09:57.320
[Guest]: So there's what's central is this woman's desire, her right to desire, her right to

01:09:57.320 --> 01:09:58.760
[Guest]: affection and love.

01:09:58.760 --> 01:10:02.760
[Guest]: And that is something that scandalized a lot of people later in the 19th century.

01:10:02.760 --> 01:10:06.440
[Guest]: So much so that the first person to try and translate her and resurrect Muddupalli again

01:10:06.440 --> 01:10:09.720
[Guest]: in the late 19th century, changed her name to Muddupalli.

01:10:09.720 --> 01:10:14.280
[Guest]: Because you know, if you pretend it's a man writing about these things, it's still a little

01:10:14.280 --> 01:10:18.040
[Guest]: acceptable in society to pretend that a woman wrote this, a woman is talking openly about

01:10:18.040 --> 01:10:22.680
[Guest]: sex and desire in the 18th century, that people would have found completely scandalizing.

01:10:22.680 --> 01:10:26.000
[Guest]: There was this critic who said that, you know, her Sanskrit is great, you know, there is

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:27.680
[Guest]: charm in her verses and so on.

01:10:27.680 --> 01:10:30.000
[Guest]: But essentially, he ended up saying that she's a whore.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:33.200
[Guest]: You can't take her words too seriously, you know, what is she talking?

01:10:33.200 --> 01:10:37.160
[Guest]: The content is horrible, even if the language and the sentences are beautiful, what she's

01:10:37.160 --> 01:10:39.040
[Guest]: expressing is scandalous.

01:10:39.040 --> 01:10:40.040
[Guest]: Critics have always been assholes.

01:10:40.040 --> 01:10:41.040
[Amit Varma]: Critics are not very pleasant people.

01:10:41.040 --> 01:10:45.640
[Amit Varma]: And you know, it's a devdasi who finally resurrects her.

01:10:45.640 --> 01:10:48.600
[Guest]: And even then the book is banned and there's, you know, all of that happening.

01:10:48.600 --> 01:10:53.520
[Guest]: It takes laughter independence for the story to be, to again, come back into the mainstream.

01:10:53.520 --> 01:10:58.160
[Guest]: Even then it's only in the 80s, where two lady scholars were writing this huge collection

01:10:58.160 --> 01:11:00.760
[Guest]: of Indian women and their place in literature.

01:11:00.760 --> 01:11:01.760
[Guest]: And they're trying to resurrect her.

01:11:01.760 --> 01:11:04.760
[Guest]: And they also run into lots of barriers where people are embarrassed or ashamed to talk

01:11:04.760 --> 01:11:05.760
[Guest]: about her and so on.

01:11:05.760 --> 01:11:08.120
[Guest]: But clearly, Muddu Pawni, at the time, she was a gem.

01:11:08.120 --> 01:11:11.480
[Guest]: She was respected by the Maratha king.

01:11:11.480 --> 01:11:14.460
[Guest]: She was a very prominent figure in his court.

01:11:14.460 --> 01:11:18.120
[Guest]: And she in her own preamble before the work talks about how famous and how celebrated

01:11:18.120 --> 01:11:22.320
[Guest]: she is as a courtesan, as well as as a creative professional.

01:11:22.320 --> 01:11:25.040
[Guest]: But clearly in one century, things can change.

01:11:25.040 --> 01:11:29.040
[Amit Varma]: And is it unusual in itself that a woman was writing Sanskrit verses like back in the day,

01:11:29.040 --> 01:11:33.480
[Guest]: like it wasn't too, this wasn't in Sanskrit, this was in Telugu.

01:11:33.480 --> 01:11:36.320
[Unknown]: But even the Telugu had great prestige, you know, you're talking about a literary tradition

01:11:36.320 --> 01:11:38.440
[Guest]: with a thousand years behind it.

01:11:38.440 --> 01:11:43.840
[Guest]: But devdasi, it's not unusual, because devdasis were literate, they were well educated, they

01:11:43.840 --> 01:11:44.840
[Guest]: had creative tastes.

01:11:44.840 --> 01:11:46.560
[Guest]: And that was promoted at one time.

01:11:46.560 --> 01:11:50.960
[Guest]: It was only by the late Victorian era, even Viceroy's, etc, you know, there's a story

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:55.640
[Guest]: of how one of these Viceroy's came to inaugurate a bridge or something.

01:11:55.640 --> 01:11:58.320
[Guest]: And he was treated to this natch performance and all of that.

01:11:58.320 --> 01:12:01.720
[Guest]: And one of the performers was MS Subbulakshmi's grandmother or great grandmother or one of

01:12:01.720 --> 01:12:02.720
[Guest]: those people.

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:06.000
[Guest]: Because even in the British period, they used to have natch performances, they used to have

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:07.680
[Guest]: dasis coming and dancing.

01:12:07.680 --> 01:12:12.120
[Guest]: But by the late 19th century, early 20th century, there was this taboo attached to it.

01:12:12.120 --> 01:12:15.760
[Guest]: And you have the whole Rukmini Arendale phenomenon where Bharatanatyam, for example, which is

01:12:15.760 --> 01:12:21.200
[Guest]: called sadar, you invent this word Bharatanatyam, or you find it from some obscure corner, because

01:12:21.200 --> 01:12:26.320
[Guest]: it suddenly sounds more Sanskritic, it sounds more chaste, you remove all the sensuous elements

01:12:26.320 --> 01:12:31.840
[Guest]: from the dance, you completely make it decentrous, decentralize it or whatever, I don't know

01:12:31.840 --> 01:12:33.320
[Guest]: what the word would be.

01:12:33.320 --> 01:12:38.040
[Guest]: And, you know, make it a chaste brahminical art form, because then brahminical daughters

01:12:38.040 --> 01:12:39.400
[Guest]: can also go and do it.

01:12:39.400 --> 01:12:41.440
[Guest]: So the devdasi becomes a prostitute.

01:12:41.440 --> 01:12:45.720
[Guest]: It was true that a lot of them were, you know, also selling their bodies due to various reasons

01:12:45.720 --> 01:12:49.640
[Guest]: it was true that their notions of sexual propriety were very different, but it was a change in

01:12:49.640 --> 01:12:53.000
[Guest]: morality that eventually made the devdasi tradition fade.

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:58.920
[Guest]: And that was it was also that same phenomenon that caused a muddhupalani to suddenly become

01:12:58.920 --> 01:13:03.000
[Guest]: some sort of receptacle of sin rather than a creative figure who actually achieved something

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:04.000
[Guest]: in the 18th century.

01:13:04.000 --> 01:13:09.720
[Amit Varma]: And is there somewhere where we can actually, like, does the original non-desexualized version

01:13:09.720 --> 01:13:10.720
[Guest]: of Bharatanatyam still exist?

01:13:10.720 --> 01:13:16.120
[Guest]: I think, you know, Balasaraswati comes from a devdasi tradition, she continued that.

01:13:16.120 --> 01:13:21.200
[Guest]: In Bangalore, a few days ago at dinner, I met a lady whose family, she learned Bharatanatyam

01:13:21.200 --> 01:13:26.200
[Guest]: from one of these old families that had Nata owners and they still teach in that old tradition.

01:13:26.200 --> 01:13:30.400
[Guest]: But real influence, what you learn in the big cities often is the Arundel school or

01:13:30.400 --> 01:13:37.000
[Guest]: the desexualized, decentralized version of Bharatanatyam.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:42.040
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of move on now to the courtesan who I assumed was the subject of your title

01:13:42.040 --> 01:13:44.080
[Amit Varma]: because she is just spectacular.

01:13:44.080 --> 01:13:48.440
[Amit Varma]: Your chapter is called the courtesan who became a princess and this obviously is Begum Sumru.

01:13:48.440 --> 01:13:54.460
[Amit Varma]: And I'll just quote this incredible line from your first paragraph on her.

01:13:54.460 --> 01:13:58.920
[Amit Varma]: She had launched her career as a dancing girl, not only rising to become the Begum of Sardana,

01:13:58.920 --> 01:14:04.320
[Amit Varma]: but also to win the affection of the Mughal emperor who styled her Zebun Nissa, jewel

01:14:04.320 --> 01:14:11.160
[Amit Varma]: among women, Farzand-e-Azizi, beloved daughter, and even Umtat-al-Arakin, pillar of the state.

01:14:11.160 --> 01:14:16.400
[Amit Varma]: She had spent her youth by the side of a much older German lover, inheriting his fortune

01:14:16.400 --> 01:14:20.640
[Amit Varma]: and lands, and later joined a Frenchman in a doomed marriage.

01:14:20.640 --> 01:14:21.640
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:14:21.640 --> 01:14:24.840
[Amit Varma]: And like you said at the start of the episode, there was also an Irish man somewhere in there.

01:14:24.840 --> 01:14:28.600
[Guest]: And when she married a Frenchman, her troops didn't like it very much.

01:14:28.600 --> 01:14:32.880
[Guest]: So she, they tied her to a gun and left her out for days in the sun.

01:14:32.880 --> 01:14:35.240
[Guest]: And this was a big summer in North India and left her there.

01:14:35.240 --> 01:14:39.520
[Guest]: So, you know, it wasn't easy at all, even with your own armies and all of that, when

01:14:39.520 --> 01:14:42.800
[Guest]: you're a woman, these men have expectations and they, I mean, one of the reasons was she

01:14:42.800 --> 01:14:43.800
[Guest]: didn't marry the right officer.

01:14:43.800 --> 01:14:46.800
[Guest]: It wasn't that she'd married a Frenchman, it was that he wasn't liked very much.

01:14:46.800 --> 01:14:50.360
[Guest]: He was a very unpopular character who had showed up somewhere in the middle.

01:14:50.360 --> 01:14:53.440
[Guest]: And you know, when she married him, they didn't quite approve of it.

01:14:53.440 --> 01:14:54.440
[Guest]: And they killed him, right?

01:14:54.440 --> 01:14:55.440
[Guest]: Yeah, he was shot.

01:14:55.440 --> 01:14:59.360
[Guest]: Some say she had a role in it, that it was all, you know, she'd conspired to end that

01:14:59.360 --> 01:15:00.360
[Guest]: way.

01:15:00.360 --> 01:15:02.360
[Guest]: But yeah, he ended up dying quite badly.

01:15:02.360 --> 01:15:07.400
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, just reading about her adventures, I mean, I thought this is like a 18th century

01:15:07.400 --> 01:15:10.320
[Amit Varma]: Bonnie and Clyde kind of situation.

01:15:10.320 --> 01:15:13.200
[Guest]: Her husband was most wanted by the British, you know, till he died.

01:15:13.200 --> 01:15:17.400
[Guest]: In fact, they were very upset when he died, quietly, because they always wanted to capture

01:15:17.400 --> 01:15:18.400
[Guest]: him.

01:15:18.400 --> 01:15:22.840
[Guest]: Because he'd massacred a number of Englishmen earlier in the 18th century, in the mid 18th

01:15:22.840 --> 01:15:23.840
[Amit Varma]: century.

01:15:23.840 --> 01:15:27.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, he massacred, as you describe it, of dozens of Englishmen in Patna.

01:15:27.120 --> 01:15:31.440
[Amit Varma]: The prisoners were invited to dinner and after his guests were in full security, protected

01:15:31.440 --> 01:15:36.160
[Amit Varma]: as they imagined by the laws of hospitality, he ordered his men to fall upon them and cut

01:15:36.160 --> 01:15:40.880
[Amit Varma]: their throats, stop quote, which almost seems a sort of a banal way of killing someone just

01:15:40.880 --> 01:15:41.880
[Guest]: cutting.

